{"title_page": "Kaechon internment camp", "text_new": "{{short description|Slave labor camp in North Korea}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{disputed|date=January 2015}}\n{{Copy edit|for=NPOV and tone|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|context=north\n|hangul=\uac1c\ucc9c \uc81c14\ud638 \uad00\ub9ac\uc18c\n|hanja={{linktext|\u4ef7|\u5ddd|\u7b2c|\u5341|\u56db|\u865f|\u7ba1|\u7406|\u6240|}}\n|rr=Gaecheon Je14ho Gwalliso\n|mr=Kaech\u014fn Che14ho Kwalliso\n|othername1=\n|hangul1=\uac1c\ucc9c \uc815\uce58\ubc94\uc218\uc6a9\uc18c\n|hanja1={{linktext|\u4ef7|\u5ddd|\u653f|\u6cbb|\u72af|\u6536|\u5bb9|\u6240|}}\n|rr1= Gaecheon Jeongchibeom Suyongso\n|mr1= Kaech\u014fn Ch\u014fngch'ib\u014fm Suyongso}}\n{{Human Rights in North Korea|expanded=Political Prisons (Kwalliso)}}\n'''Kaechon internment camp''' ([[Hangeul]]: {{lang|ko-Hang|\uac1c\ucc9c \uc81c14\ud638 \uad00\ub9ac\uc18c}}, also spelled '''Kae'ch\u014fn''' or ''Gaecheon'') is a labor camp in [[North Korea]] for political prisoners and descendants of alleged criminals. The official name for the camp is '''[[Kwalliso|Kwan-li-so]] (Penal-labor colony) No. 14'''. The camp is commonly known as '''Camp 14'''. It is not to be confused with the [[Kaechon concentration camp]] (Kyo-hwa-so No. 1), which is located {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the northwest. \n\n==Description==\n{{location map+|North Korea|caption = Location of Kaechon camp in North Korea| float=right|width=|places=\n{{location map~|North Korea|label=Pyongyang|position=bottom|lat=39.063457|long=125.789200|region=KP-01|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{location map~|North Korea|label=Kaechon|position=top|lat=39.571086|long=126.055466|region=KP-02}}}}\n\nThe camp was established around 1959<ref name=\"Harden\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/mar/16/escape-north-korea-prison-camp |title=How one man escaped from a North Korean prison camp |author=Blaine Harden |date=16 March 2012 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=4 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509181622/http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2012/mar/16/escape-north-korea-prison-camp |archivedate=May 9, 2012 }}</ref> in central North Korea near [[Kaechon|Kae'ch\u014fn county]], [[P'y\u014fngan-namdo|South Pyongan Province]]. It is situated along the middle reaches of the [[Taedong River|Taedong]] river, which forms the southern boundary of the camp, and includes the mountains north of the river, including Purok-san. [[Bukchang concentration camp|Bukchang]], a concentration camp (Kwan-li-so No. 18) adjoins the southern banks of the [[Taedong River]]. The camp is about {{convert|155|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} in area, with farms, mines and factories threaded through the steep mountain valleys.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=Committee for Human Rights in North Korea: Satellite Imagery of the North Korean Gulag: Kwan-li-so No. 14 Kaechon Overview, p. 209|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-12-07}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ned.org/about/board/meet-our-president/archived-presentations-and-articles/north-korean-human-rights-prison- North Korean Human Rights: Prison Camps in 2012...], ned.org; accessed October 30, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/19/AR2009071902178.html|work=The Washington Post|first=Blaine|last=Harden|title=N. Korea's Hard-Labor Camps: On the Diplomatic Back Burner|date=July 20, 2009}}</ref> The camp includes overcrowded barracks that house males, females, and older children separately, a headquarters with administrative buildings and guard housing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=Committee for Human Rights in North Korea: Satellite Imagery of the North Korean Gulag: Kwan-li-so No. 14 Kaechon Headquarters|page=211|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-12-07}}</ref> Altogether around 15,000 prisoners live in Kaechon internment camp.<ref name=\"hrnk.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=Committee for Human Rights in North Korea: The Hidden Gulag (Section: Testimony Kwan-li-so No. 14 Kaechon, p. 48)|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==Purpose==\nThe main purpose of the Kaechon internment camp is to keep politically unreliable persons classed \"unredeemable\"<ref name=\"Harden\"/> isolated from society and to exploit their labor.<ref>{{citation|title=Prison Camps of North Korea - Camp 14 Kaechon|work=U.S. State Department Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor|url=http://www.humanrights.gov/features/prison-camps-of-north-korea/camp-14-kaechon/|accessdate=January 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514205337/http://www.humanrights.gov/features/prison-camps-of-north-korea/camp-14-kaechon/|archive-date=May 14, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title= Torture, starvation, infant execution in N. Korea prison camps exposed to UN panel |work=RT (Russia Today)|date=August 20, 2013|url=http://rt.com/news/un-north-korea-torture-732/| accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref> Those sent to the camp include officials perceived to have performed poorly in their job, people who criticize the regime, their children, anyone who was born in the camp, and anyone suspected of engaging in \"anti-government\" activities.<ref>{{cite web | title= End horror of North Korean political prison camps|work=Amnesty International  |date=May 4, 2011| url= https://www.amnesty.org/en/appeals-for-action/north-korean-political-prison-camps | accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref> Prisoners have to work in one of the coal mines, and in one of the factories that produce textiles, paper, food, rubber, shoes, ceramics, and cement or in agriculture. Livestock raising is considered the occupation of choice for the prisoners as it gives them the chance to steal animal food and pick through animal droppings for undigested grains. <ref name=\"hrnk.org\"/>\n\n==Human rights situation==\nWitnesses have reported that prisoners interred in the camp are required to work for long periods of time, often from 5:30 to midnight.<ref>{{cite web|author=Yang Jung A|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk02500&num=2313|title=My Mother is Executed. Yet I am not sad.|publisher=Daily NK|date=2007-07-03|accessdate=2012-12-10}}</ref> Even 11-year-old children have to work after school and thus rarely see their parents.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/09/world/asia/09iht-korea.4.6569853.html?pagewanted=2&_r=2|work=The New York Times|first=Choe|last=Sang-Hun|title=Born and raised in a North Korean gulag|date=July 9, 2007}}</ref> Other reports describe prisoners being beaten and severely punished for minor infractions.<ref name=\"Anderson Cooper\">{{cite news|work=60 Minutes Overtime|author=Anderson Cooper|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/un-witness-describes-horrors-of-north-korea|title=UN witness describes horrors of North Korea (Anderson Cooper\u2019s remarkable interview with Shin Dong-hyuk, who was born in \"Camp 14\", a North Korean gulag described in a UN Human Rights report)|date=February 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Shin Dong-Hyuk|url=http://www.rfa.org/english/news/korea/book-11162008180959.html/extracts-11192008085805.html|title=\"A Glimpse of Horror\", Radio Free Asia|date=December 1, 2008|publisher=Rfa.org|accessdate=2012-12-07}}</ref>\n\nFood rations are scant, consisting of salted cabbage and corn. The prisoners are emaciated; they lose their teeth, and their gums blacken.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/19/AR2009071902178.html|work=The Washington Post|first=Blaine|last=Harden|title=N. Korea's Hard-Labor Camps: On the Diplomatic Back Burner|date=July 20, 2009}}</ref> Many die of malnourishment, illness, work accidents, and the aftereffects of torture. Many prisoners resort to eating frogs, insects, rats, snakes, and even  cannibalism in order to try to survive.<ref name=\"Harden\"/><ref name=\"Anderson Cooper\"/> Eating rat flesh helps prevent [[pellagra]], a common disease in the camp resulting from the absence of protein and [[niacin]] in the diet. In order to eat anything outside of the prison-sanctioned meal, including these animals, prisoners must first get permission from the guards.<ref name=\"Harden\"/>\n\n===Imprisoned witnesses===\n====Shin Dong-hyuk====\nIn his official biography ''Escape from Camp 14'' by [[Blaine Harden]], [[Shin Dong-hyuk]] claimed that he was born in the camp and lived there until escaping in his early twenties. In 2015, Shin recanted some of this story.<ref name=\"Fifield\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/prominent-n-korean-defector-shin-dong-hyuk-admits-parts-of-story-are-inaccurate/2015/01/17/fc69278c-9dd5-11e4-bcfb-059ec7a93ddc_story.html|author=Anna Fifield|title=Prominent N. Korean defector Shin Dong-hyuk admits parts of story are inaccurate|newspaper=Washington Post|date=17 January 2015}}</ref> Shin told Harden that he had changed some dates and locations and incorporated some \"fictive elements\" into his account. Harden outlined these revisions in a new foreword but did not revise the entire book. Shin said that he did not spend his entire North Korean life at Camp 14. Though maintaining that he was born there, he stated that, when he was young, his family was transferred to the less severe [[Pukchang concentration camp|Camp 18]], and spent several years there. He said that he was tortured in Camp 14 in 2002, as punishment for escaping from Camp 18.<ref name=\"Blaine Harden, Author and Journalist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blaineharden.com/|title=A new Foreword to ''Escape from Camp 14''|work=blaineharden.com|author=Harden, Blaine|date=2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nknews.org/2015/03/author-of-book-on-north-koreas-founding-addresses-shin-controversy/ |title=Author of book on North Korea\u2019s founding addresses Shin controversy |work=NK News|author=John Power |date=March 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Kim Yong====\nKim Yong (1995\u20131996 in Kaechon, then in Bukchang) was imprisoned after it was revealed that the two men who were executed as alleged US spies were his father and brother.<ref name=\"hrnk.org\"/> He witnessed approximately 25 executions in his section of the camp within less than two years.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hidden Gulag \u2013 Exposing Crimes against Humanity in North Korea\u2019s Vast Prison System (pp. 51-52)|work=The Committee for Human Rights in North Korea|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|accessdate=April 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\n* ''[[Camp 14: Total Control Zone]]''\n* [[Human rights in North Korea]]\n* [[Kaechon concentration camp]]\n* [[Prisons in North Korea]]\n* [[Pukchang concentration camp]]\n* [[Slavery]]\n* [[Yodok concentration camp]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Blaine Harden|title=Escape from Camp 14: One Man's Remarkable Odyssey from North Korea to Freedom in the West|publisher=Viking|date=March 29, 2012|type=HC (hardcover)|isbn=978-0670023325}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/CoIDPRK/Pages/ReportoftheCommissionofInquiryDPRK.aspx United Nations Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights] \u2013 Report of the Commission of Inquiry on Human Rights in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea\n*[https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/asa24/001/2011/en/ North Korea: Political Prison Camps] - Amnesty International document on conditions in North Korean prison camps (May 2011).\n* {{cite web|website=HRNK.org|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=Committee for Human Rights in North Korea] \u2013 Overview on North Korean Prison Camps with Testimonies and Satellite Photographs}}\n* {{cite web|website=NorthKoreanRefugees.com|date=September 2007|url=http://www.northkoreanrefugees.com/2007-09-atbirth.htm|title=Life Funds for North Korean Refugees (NGO): Political prisoner Shin Dong-hyuk tells about his life in the camp}} \n* {{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/09/world/asia/09iht-korea.4.6569853.html|title=Born and raised in a North Korean gulag|work= New York Times|date=July 7, 2007}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/12/10/AR2008121003855.html |title=Escapee Tells of Horrors in North Korean Prison Camp|work= Washington Post|date=December 11, 2008}}\n* {{cite web|website=Eng.NKHumanRights.or.kr|url=http://eng.nkhumanrights.or.kr/board/bbs_list.php?board_table=bbs_evidence |title=Citizens' Alliance for North Korean Human Rights}} Witness accounts by North Korean refugees\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=2051|title=Escape from 'Total Control Zone' - North Korea's Papillon|work=The Daily NK|date=May 11, 2007|access-date=April 15, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716084531/http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=2051|archive-date=July 16, 2011|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://freekorea.us/camps/14-18|title=One Free Korea: Camps 14 and 18, North Korea: Satellite Imagery|website=FreeKorea.us}} Detailed satellite images with comprehensive explanations\n\n{{coord|39.571086|N|126.055466|E|region:KP-PYN_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title }}\n\n{{Political prison camps of North Korea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaechon Internment Camp}}\n[[Category:Concentration camps in North Korea]]\n[[Category:Incidents of cannibalism]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Slave labor camp in North Korea}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{disputed|date=January 2015}}\n{{Copy edit|for=NPOV and tone|date=April 2020}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n|context=north\n|hangul=\uac1c\ucc9c \uc81c14\ud638 \uad00\ub9ac\uc18c\n|hanja={{linktext|\u4ef7|\u5ddd|\u7b2c|\u5341|\u56db|\u865f|\u7ba1|\u7406|\u6240|}}\n|rr=Gaecheon Je14ho Gwalliso\n|mr=Kaech\u014fn Che14ho Kwalliso\n|othername1=\n|hangul1=\uac1c\ucc9c \uc815\uce58\ubc94\uc218\uc6a9\uc18c\n|hanja1={{linktext|\u4ef7|\u5ddd|\u653f|\u6cbb|\u72af|\u6536|\u5bb9|\u6240|}}\n|rr1= Gaecheon Jeongchibeom Suyongso\n|mr1= Kaech\u014fn Ch\u014fngch'ib\u014fm Suyongso}}\n{{Human Rights in North Korea|expanded=Political Prisons (Kwalliso)}}\n'''Kaechon internment camp''' ([[Hangeul]]: {{lang|ko-Hang|\uac1c\ucc9c \uc81c14\ud638 \uad00\ub9ac\uc18c}}, also spelled '''Kae'ch\u014fn''' or ''Gaecheon'') is a labor camp in [[North Korea]] for political prisoners and descendants of alleged criminals. The official name for the camp is '''[[Kwalliso|Kwan-li-so]] (Penal-labor colony) No. 14'''. The camp is commonly known as '''Camp 14'''. It is not to be confused with the [[Kaechon concentration camp]] (Kyo-hwa-so No. 1), which is located {{convert|20|km|mi|abbr=on}} to the northwest. \n\n==Description==\n{{location map+|North Korea|caption = Location of Kaechon camp in North Korea| float=right|width=|places=\n{{location map~|North Korea|label=Pyongyang|position=bottom|lat=39.063457|long=125.789200|region=KP-01|mark=Blue pog.svg}}\n{{location map~|North Korea|label=Kaechon|position=top|lat=39.571086|long=126.055466|region=KP-02}}}}\n\nThe camp was established around 1959<ref name=\"Harden\">{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/mar/16/escape-north-korea-prison-camp |title=How one man escaped from a North Korean prison camp |author=Blaine Harden |date=16 March 2012 |newspaper=The Guardian |accessdate=4 February 2013 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120509181622/http://www.guardian.co.uk/books/2012/mar/16/escape-north-korea-prison-camp |archivedate=May 9, 2012 }}</ref> in central North Korea near [[Kaechon|Kae'ch\u014fn county]], [[P'y\u014fngan-namdo|South Pyongan Province]]. It is situated along the middle reaches of the [[Taedong River|Taedong]] river, which forms the southern boundary of the camp, and includes the mountains north of the river, including Purok-san. [[Bukchang concentration camp|Bukchang]], a concentration camp (Kwan-li-so No. 18) adjoins the southern banks of the [[Taedong River]]. The camp is about {{convert|155|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} in area, with farms, mines and factories threaded through the steep mountain valleys.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=Committee for Human Rights in North Korea: Satellite Imagery of the North Korean Gulag: Kwan-li-so No. 14 Kaechon Overview, p. 209|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-12-07}}</ref><ref>[http://www.ned.org/about/board/meet-our-president/archived-presentations-and-articles/north-korean-human-rights-prison- North Korean Human Rights: Prison Camps in 2012...], ned.org; accessed October 30, 2014.</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2009/07/19/AR2009071902178.html|work=The Washington Post|first=Blaine|last=Harden|title=N. Korea's Hard-Labor Camps: On the Diplomatic Back Burner|date=July 20, 2009}}</ref> The camp includes overcrowded barracks that house males, females, and older children separately, a headquarters with administrative buildings and guard housing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=Committee for Human Rights in North Korea: Satellite Imagery of the North Korean Gulag: Kwan-li-so No. 14 Kaechon Headquarters|page=211|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-12-07}}</ref> Altogether around 15,000 prisoners live in Kaechon internment camp.<ref name=\"hrnk.org\">{{cite web|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=Committee for Human Rights in North Korea: The Hidden Gulag (Section: Testimony Kwan-li-so No. 14 Kaechon, p. 48)|format=PDF|accessdate=2012-12-07}}</ref>\n\n==Purpose==\nThe main purpose of the Kaechon internment camp is to keep politically unreliable persons classed \"unredeemable\"<ref name=\"Harden\"/> isolated from society and to exploit their labor.<ref>{{citation|title=Prison Camps of North Korea - Camp 14 Kaechon|work=U.S. State Department Bureau of Democracy, Human Rights and Labor|url=http://www.humanrights.gov/features/prison-camps-of-north-korea/camp-14-kaechon/|accessdate=January 15, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150514205337/http://www.humanrights.gov/features/prison-camps-of-north-korea/camp-14-kaechon/|archive-date=May 14, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{citation|title= Torture, starvation, infant execution in N. Korea prison camps exposed to UN panel |work=RT (Russia Today)|date=August 20, 2013|url=http://rt.com/news/un-north-korea-torture-732/| accessdate=January 15, 2015}}</ref> Those sent to the camp include officials perceived to have performed poorly in their job, people who criticize the regime, their children, anyone who was born in the camp, and anyone suspected of engaging in \"anti-government\" activities.<ref>{{cite web | title= End horror of North Korean political prison camps|work=Amnesty International  |date=May 4, 2011| url= https://www.amnesty.org/en/appeals-for-action/north-korean-political-prison-camps | accessdate=January 15, 2014}}</ref> Prisoners have to work in one of the coal mines, and in one of the factories that produce textiles, paper, food, rubber, shoes, ceramics, and cement or in agriculture.<ref name=\"hrnk.org\"/>\n\n==Human rights situation==\nWitnesses have reported that prisoners interred in the camp are required to work for long periods of time, often from 5:30 to midnight.<ref>{{cite web|author=Yang Jung A|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk02500&num=2313|title=My Mother is Executed. Yet I am not sad.|publisher=Daily NK|date=2007-07-03|accessdate=2012-12-10}}</ref> Even 11-year-old children have to work after school and see their parents rarely.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/09/world/asia/09iht-korea.4.6569853.html?pagewanted=2&_r=2|work=The New York Times|first=Choe|last=Sang-Hun|title=Born and raised in a North Korean gulag|date=July 9, 2007}}</ref> Other reports describe prisoners being beaten and severely punished for minor infractions.<ref name=\"Anderson Cooper\">{{cite news|work=60 Minutes Overtime|author=Anderson Cooper|url=http://www.cbsnews.com/news/un-witness-describes-horrors-of-north-korea|title=UN witness describes horrors of North Korea (Anderson Cooper\u2019s remarkable interview with Shin Dong-hyuk, who was born in \"Camp 14\", a North Korean gulag described in a UN Human Rights report)|date=February 18, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Shin Dong-Hyuk|url=http://www.rfa.org/english/news/korea/book-11162008180959.html/extracts-11192008085805.html|title=\"A Glimpse of Horror\", Radio Free Asia|date=December 1, 2008|publisher=Rfa.org|accessdate=2012-12-07}}</ref>\n\nFood rations are very small, consisting of salted cabbage and corn so that the prisoners are very skinny and weak. Many die of malnourishment, illness, work accidents, and the aftereffects of torture. Many prisoners resort to eating frogs, insects, rats, snakes, and even resort to cannibalism in order to try to survive.<ref name=\"Harden\"/><ref name=\"Anderson Cooper\"/> Eating rat flesh helps to prevent [[pellagra]], a common disease in the camp which results from the absence of protein and [[niacin]] in the diet. In order to eat anything outside of the prison-sanctioned meal, including these animals, prisoners must first get permission from the guards.<ref name=\"Harden\"/>\n\n===Imprisoned witnesses===\n====Shin Dong-hyuk====\nIn his official biography ''Escape from Camp 14'' by [[Blaine Harden]], [[Shin Dong-hyuk]] claimed that he was born in the camp and lived there until escaping in his early twenties. In 2015, Shin recanted some of this story.<ref name=\"Fifield\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/prominent-n-korean-defector-shin-dong-hyuk-admits-parts-of-story-are-inaccurate/2015/01/17/fc69278c-9dd5-11e4-bcfb-059ec7a93ddc_story.html|author=Anna Fifield|title=Prominent N. Korean defector Shin Dong-hyuk admits parts of story are inaccurate|newspaper=Washington Post|date=17 January 2015}}</ref> Shin told Harden that he had changed some dates and locations and incorporated some \"fictive elements\" into his account. Harden outlined these revisions in a new foreword but did not revise the entire book. Shin said that he did not spend his entire North Korean life at Camp 14. Though maintaining that he was born there, he stated that, when he was young, his family was transferred to the less severe [[Pukchang concentration camp|Camp 18]], and spent several years there. He said that he was tortured in Camp 14 in 2002, as punishment for escaping from Camp 18.<ref name=\"Blaine Harden, Author and Journalist\">{{cite web|url=http://www.blaineharden.com/|title=A new Foreword to ''Escape from Camp 14''|work=blaineharden.com|author=Harden, Blaine|date=2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.nknews.org/2015/03/author-of-book-on-north-koreas-founding-addresses-shin-controversy/ |title=Author of book on North Korea\u2019s founding addresses Shin controversy |work=NK News|author=John Power |date=March 18, 2015}}</ref>\n\n====Kim Yong====\nKim Yong (1995\u20131996 in Kaechon, then in Bukchang) was imprisoned after it was revealed that two men executed as alleged US spies were his father and brother.<ref name=\"hrnk.org\"/> He witnessed approximately 25 executions in his section of the camp within less than two years.<ref>{{cite web|title=The Hidden Gulag \u2013 Exposing Crimes against Humanity in North Korea\u2019s Vast Prison System (pp. 51-52)|work=The Committee for Human Rights in North Korea|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|accessdate=April 25, 2012}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n\n<!-- New links in alphabetical order please -->\n* ''[[Camp 14: Total Control Zone]]''\n* [[Human rights in North Korea]]\n* [[Kaechon concentration camp]]\n* [[Prisons in North Korea]]\n* [[Pukchang concentration camp]]\n* [[Slavery]]\n* [[Yodok concentration camp]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*{{cite book|author=Blaine Harden|title=Escape from Camp 14: One Man's Remarkable Odyssey from North Korea to Freedom in the West|publisher=Viking|date=March 29, 2012|type=HC (hardcover)|isbn=978-0670023325}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.ohchr.org/EN/HRBodies/HRC/CoIDPRK/Pages/ReportoftheCommissionofInquiryDPRK.aspx United Nations Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights] \u2013 Report of the Commission of Inquiry on Human Rights in the Democratic People's Republic of Korea\n*[https://www.amnesty.org/en/documents/asa24/001/2011/en/ North Korea: Political Prison Camps] - Amnesty International document on conditions in North Korean prison camps (May 2011).\n* {{cite web|website=HRNK.org|url=http://www.hrnk.org/uploads/pdfs/HRNK_HiddenGulag2_Web_5-18.pdf|title=Committee for Human Rights in North Korea] \u2013 Overview on North Korean Prison Camps with Testimonies and Satellite Photographs}}\n* {{cite web|website=NorthKoreanRefugees.com|date=September 2007|url=http://www.northkoreanrefugees.com/2007-09-atbirth.htm|title=Life Funds for North Korean Refugees (NGO): Political prisoner Shin Dong-hyuk tells about his life in the camp}} \n* {{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/07/09/world/asia/09iht-korea.4.6569853.html|title=Born and raised in a North Korean gulag|work= New York Times|date=July 7, 2007}}\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2008/12/10/AR2008121003855.html |title=Escapee Tells of Horrors in North Korean Prison Camp|work= Washington Post|date=December 11, 2008}}\n* {{cite web|website=Eng.NKHumanRights.or.kr|url=http://eng.nkhumanrights.or.kr/board/bbs_list.php?board_table=bbs_evidence |title=Citizens' Alliance for North Korean Human Rights}} Witness accounts by North Korean refugees\n* {{cite news|url=http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=2051|title=Escape from 'Total Control Zone' - North Korea's Papillon|work=The Daily NK|date=May 11, 2007|access-date=April 15, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110716084531/http://www.dailynk.com/english/read.php?cataId=nk00100&num=2051|archive-date=July 16, 2011|url-status=dead}}\n* {{cite web|url=http://freekorea.us/camps/14-18|title=One Free Korea: Camps 14 and 18, North Korea: Satellite Imagery|website=FreeKorea.us}} Detailed satellite images with comprehensive explanations\n\n{{coord|39.571086|N|126.055466|E|region:KP-PYN_type:landmark|format=dms|display=title }}\n\n{{Political prison camps of North Korea}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kaechon Internment Camp}}\n[[Category:Concentration camps in North Korea]]\n[[Category:Incidents of cannibalism]]\n", "name_user": "Rex ebrea", "label": "safe", "comment": "I rephrased a couple sentences for better clarity, and I visited some of the links to verify facts and add a few details.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Kaechon_internment_camp"}
{"title_page": "National Liberal Party (Romania)", "text_new": "{{About|the modern political party|the historical party|National Liberal Party (Romania, 1875)}}\n{{Other uses|National Liberal Party (disambiguation){{!}}National Liberal Party}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2011}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| name = National Liberal Party\n| logo = National Liberal Party Romania.png\n| colorcode = {{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}\n| president = [[Ludovic Orban]]\n| secretary_general = {{ill|Robert-Ionatan Sighiart\u0103u|ro}}\n| ideology = [[Conservative liberalism]]<br>[[Liberal conservatism]]<br>[[Pro-Europeanism]]<ref name =\"afiliere internationala\">https://pnl.ro/afiliere-internationala/</ref>\n| headquarters = Modrogan nr 1, [[Sector 1 (Bucharest)|Sector 1]], [[Bucharest]], [[Romania]]\n| international = {{nowrap|[[Centrist Democrat International]]}}\n| website = {{URL|https://pnl.ro}}\n| country = Romania\n| native_name = Partidul Na\u021bional Liberal\n| native_name_lang = ro\n| abbreviation = PNL\n| leader1_title = Leader in the [[Senate of Romania|Senate]]\n| leader1_name = {{ill|C\u0103t\u0103lin-Daniel Fenechiu|ro}}\n| leader2_title = Leader in the [[Chamber of Deputies (Romania)|Chamber of Deputies]]\n| leader2_name = {{ill|Florin Roman|ro}}\n| leader3_title = Leader in the [[European Parliament]]\n| leader3_name = [[Rare\u0219 Bogdan]]\n| founded = {{ubl|{{start date and age|1875|5|24|df=y}}<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books/about/Enciclopedia_partidelor_politice_din_Rom.html?id=Jck4AAAAMAAJ&redir_esc=y|title=Enciclopedia partidelor politice din Rom\u00e2nia, 1859-2003|publisher=Meronia|last=Scurtu|first=Ioan|location=Bucharest|year=2003|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n|15 January 1990 {{small|(re-established after the [[Romanian Revolution]])}}<ref>{{cite book|author=Iv\u00e1n Zolt\u00e1n D\u00e9nes|title=Liberty and the Search for Identity: Liberal Nationalisms and the Legacy of Empires|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vgJs0UVwdBQC&pg=PA383|year=2006|publisher=Central European University Press|isbn=978-963-7326-44-8|page=383}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pnl.ro/pagina/scurt-istoric|title=Scurt istoric|work=PNL|language=Romanian|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141215050928/http://www.pnl.ro/pagina/scurt-istoric|archivedate=15 December 2014|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n|6 October 2014 {{small|(merger with [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|PDL]])}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hotnews.ro/stiri-politic-18249777-tribunalul-bucuresti-admis-fuziunea-prin-contopire-dintre-pnl-pdl.htm|title=Tribunalul Bucure\u0219ti a admis fuziunea prin contopire dintre PNL \u0219i PDL|work=HotNews.ro|last=Neagu|first=Alina |date=6 October 2014|language=Romanian}}</ref>}}\n| student_wing = [[Liberal Student Clubs (Romania)|Liberal Student Clubs]] (CSL)\n| youth_wing = [[National Liberal Youth (Romania)|National Liberal Youth]] (TNL)\n| womens_wing = [[Liberal Women Organisation (Romania)|Liberal Women National Organisation]] (ONFL)\n| membership_year = 2018\n| membership = 253,895<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thenewfederalist.eu/top-30-partide-politice-din-romania|title=Top 30 partide politice din Rom\u00e2nia|work=The New Federalist|last=Matache|first=Narcis George|date=3 May 2018|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n| position = [[Centrism|Centre]]<ref>{{cite news |date= 27 June 2018 |title= Romanian government defeats no-confidence vote as thousands protest |url= https://www.irishtimes.com/news/world/europe/romanian-government-defeats-no-confidence-vote-as-thousands-protest-1.3546016 |work= [[The Irish Times]]|agency=[[Reuters]] |access-date= 30 April 2019}}</ref> to [[Centre-right politics|centre-right]]<ref>{{cite book|author1=Lavinia Stan|author2=Rodica Zaharia|chapter=Romania|editor1=Donnacha \u00d3 Beach\u00e1in|editor2=Vera Sheridan|editor3=Sabina Stan|title=Life in Post-communist Eastern Europe After EU Membership: Happy Ever After?|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ms-2PaKTA4sC&pg=PA188|year=2012|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-0-415-68084-4|page=188}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |date= 9 December 2016 |title= Graft-tainted Romanian left eyes election comeback |url= https://www.euractiv.com/section/elections/news/graft-tainted-romanian-left-eyes-election-comeback/ |work= EURACTIV |access-date= 30 April 2019}}</ref>\n| national = \n| european = [[European People's Party]]\n| europarl = [[European People's Party group|European People's Party]]\n| colors = {{color box|{{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}|border=darkgray}} Yellow<br>{{color box|#0068A8|border=darkgray}} Blue\n| slogan = ''Prin noi \u00een\u0219ine!''<br>(\"Through Ourselves!\")\n| anthem = \"Verde-nrourat\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digi24.ro/Stiri/Digi24/Actualitate/Politica/Intelegere+politica+PDL+da+sediul+si+imnul+PNL+numele+noului+par|title=\u00cen\u021belegere politic\u0103 pentru noul partid de dreapta. PNL \u0219i PDL vor c\u00e2nta de acum \"Verde-nrourat\"|work=Digi24|date=17 August 2014|language=Romanian}}</ref><br>{{small|\"Dewy Green\"}}\n| seats1_title = [[Senate of Romania|Senate]]\n| seats1 = {{Composition bar|31|136|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}<ref name=\"2016 legislative election results\">{{cite news|url=http://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/politica/alegeri-parlamentare-2016/rezultate-finale-psd-221-de-mandate-pnl-99-de-mandate-632969|title=Rezultate finale. PSD - 221 de mandate, PNL - 99 de mandate|publisher=DIgi24|date=15 December 2016|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n| seats2_title = [[Chamber of Deputies (Romania)|Chamber of Deputies]]\n| seats2 = {{Composition bar|82|329|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}<ref name=\"2016 legislative election results\"/>\n| seats3_title = [[European Parliament]]\n| seats3 = {{Composition bar|10|33|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}\n| seats4_title = Mayors\n| seats4 = {{Composition bar|1066|3186|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}<ref name=\"2016 local election results\">[http://www.2016bec.ro/wp-content/uploads/2016/06/SIAL2016_Situatia_mandatelor_partide-2.xlsx BEC - Situa\u021bia mandatelor pe partide (in Romanian)]</ref><ref name=\"pnl.ro\">[https://pnl.ro/ Partidul Na\u021bional Liberal (in Romanian)]</ref>\n| seats5_title = [[Counties of Romania|County]] Councilors\n| seats5 = {{Composition bar|504|1434|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}<ref name=\"2016 local election results\"/>\n| seats6_title = Local Council Councilors\n| seats6 = {{Composition bar|13697|40067|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}<ref name=\"2016 local election results\"/><ref name=\"pnl.ro\"/>\n| flag = \n| footnotes = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cdep.ro/pls/parlam/structura.gp|title=Grupurile parlamentare|work=Chamber of Deputies|language=Romanian}}</ref>\n}}\n\nThe '''National Liberal Party''' ({{lang-ro|Partidul Na\u021bional Liberal}}, '''PNL''') is a [[conservative liberalism|conservative]]-[[liberalism and radicalism in Romania|liberal]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Caroline Close|chapter=The liberal family ideology: Distinct, but diverse|editor1=Emilie van Haute|editor2=Caroline Close|title=Liberal Parties in Europe|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=6zuIDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA344|year=2019|publisher=Taylor & Francis|isbn=978-1-351-24549-4|page=344}}</ref> and [[liberal conservatism|liberal conservative]]<ref>{{cite web|first=Wolfram|last=Nordsieck|url=http://www.parties-and-elections.eu/romania.html|title=Romania|website=Parties and Elections in Europe|year=2016|accessdate=19 August 2018}}</ref> [[list of political parties in Romania|political party in Romania]]. Refounded in 1990, it claims the legacy of the major [[National Liberal Party (Romania, 1875)|political party of the same name]], active between 1875 and the late 1940s in the [[Kingdom of Romania]]. Based on this legacy, it often presents itself as the first formally constituted political party in the country and the oldest party from the family of European liberal parties.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.agerpres.ro/politica/2013/05/24/antonescu-la-138-de-ani-de-la-infiintarea-sa-destinul-pnl-este-strans-legat-de-evolutia-romaniei-si-de-parcursul-european-10-13-08 |title=Antonescu: La 138 de ani de la \u00eenfiin\u021barea sa destinul PNL este str\u00e2ns legat de evolu\u021bia Rom\u00e2niei \u0219i de parcursul european |work=Agerpres |date=24 May 2013 |language=ro}}</ref>\n\nUntil 2014, the PNL was a member of the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Party|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] (ALDE).<ref>{{cite book|author=Donatella M. Viola|title=Routledge Handbook of European Elections|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7stgCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA665|year=2015|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-50363-7|page=665}}</ref> The party statutes adopted in June 2014 dropped any reference to international affiliation, consequently most of its [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s joined the [[European People's Party group]] (EPP) in the [[European Parliament]].\n\nOn 12 September 2014, it was admitted as a full member of the [[European People's Party]],<ref>{{Cite web |title=EPP concerned over actions of radical Islamic militant groups and over latest political developments in Romania; welcomes five new member parties |publisher=European People's Party |date=12 September 2014 |url=http://www.epp.eu/epp-concerned-over-actions-radical-islamic-militant-groups-and-over-latest-political-developments |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150413072435/http://www.epp.eu/epp-concerned-over-actions-radical-islamic-militant-groups-and-over-latest-political-developments |archivedate=13 April 2015 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> and subsequently merged with the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]]. The party was also a member of the [[Liberal International]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.liberal-international.org/site/Full_Members.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2016-05-21 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140525043836/http://www.liberal-international.org/site/Full_Members.html |archivedate=25 May 2014 |df=dmy-all }}</ref> before switching to [[Centrist Democrat International]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://idc-cdi.com/en/parties|title=Centrist Democrat International - Member parties|accessdate=17 April 2020}}</ref> Currently, it is the second-largest party in the [[Parliament of Romania|Romanian Parliament]], with 82 seats in the [[Chamber of Deputies (Romania)|Chamber of Deputies]] and 31 in the [[Senate of Romania|Senate]], behind the opposition [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party]] (PSD).\n\n== Recent history==\n\n=== 1990\u20132000: Re-foundation and first governing experiences ===\n\n{{Main|National Liberal Party (Romania, 1875)|Liberalism and radicalism in Romania}}\n\n[[File:PNL years 90.png|thumb|left|Liberal political groups integrated within the National Liberal Party during the 1990s.]]\n\nThe National Liberal Party of Romania was re-founded in January, 1990, a few days after the end of the [[Romanian Revolution|1989 Romanian revolution]]. At that time, the party revolved around two political leaders such as [[Radu C\u00e2mpeanu]] and [[Mircea Ionescu-Quintus]], both former youth liberal leaders during the [[interwar period]] and after [[World War II]]. At the [[1990 Romanian general election|1990 general elections]], the PNL became the third largest party in Romania and its then leader, Radu C\u00e2mpeanu, finished second in the same year's presidential elections, with 10.6% of the cast votes, behind [[Ion Iliescu]].\n\nShortly afterwards, most notably alongside the [[Christian Democratic National Peasants' Party]] (PN\u021a-CD), but to a lesser extent also with other smaller center-right parties and NGOs, the PNL managed to form the [[Romanian Democratic Convention]] (CDR) in an effort to ensemble a stronger collective opposition and alternative governing body to then ruling [[National Salvation Front (Romania)|National Salvation Front]] (FSN). However, prior to the [[1992 Romanian general election|1992 general elections]], C\u00e2mpeanu decided to withdraw the party from the CDR electoral alliance and instead compete as a stand-alone political force.\n\nUltimately, this proved to be a strategic error, as the party did not manage to surpass the needed electoral threshold for parliamentary presence and as such was forced to enter extra-parliamentary opposition for the period 1992\u20131996. This also resulted in several splinter factions leaving the main party, with some PNL groups opting to remain within the CDR while others still supporting C\u00e2mpeanu's side.\n\nNevertheless, after a change of leadership that saw Ionescu-Quintus as the new party leader elected in 1995, the PNL contested the [[1996 Romanian general election|1996 general election]] as part of the CDR.<ref name=\"RoseMunro2009\">{{cite book|author1=Richard Rose|author2=Neil Munro|title=Parties and Elections in New European Democracies|year=2009|publisher=ECPR Press|isbn=978-0-9558203-2-8|pages=215\u2013216}}</ref> The 1996 general elections represented the first peaceful transition of power in post-1989 Romania, with the PNL, PN\u021a-CD, [[Democratic Party (Romania)|Democratic Party]] (PD), and the [[Democratic Alliance of Hungarians in Romania]] (UDMR) forming a grand coalition that pushed the PDSR (formerly the FSN) in opposition for the period 1996\u20132000. The presidency was also won by the CDR's common candidate, more specifically [[Emil Constantinescu]], who received support on behalf of all of the alliance's constituent parties (including the PNL political groups therein).\n\n=== 2000\u20132010: Opposition and second governing experiences ===\n\nBetween 1996 and 2000, because of the lack of political coherence within the parties of the governing CDR coalition and the multiple changes of cabinets that followed, the PNL decided once more to withdraw from the alliance just before the [[2000 Romanian general election|2000 general elections]] and, consequently, to compete alone instead. This time, the party managed to gain parliamentary presence but failed to form another centre-right government, finishing fourth in the legislative elections and third in the presidential election.\n\nTherefore, during the mid 2000s, the PNL joined forces with the PD in order to form the [[Justice and Truth Alliance]] (DA)<ref name=\"RoseMunro2009\"/> so as to compete in the [[2004 Romanian general election|2004 general election]] as an alternative to the then ruling PSD (formerly PDSR) government. The alliance managed to finish second by popular vote in the [[Parliament of Romania|Parliament]], subsequently form a centre-right cabinet, and also win the presidency during the same year.\n\nUntil April 2007, the PNL was the largest member of the governing Justice and Truth Alliance, which enjoyed a parliamentary majority due to an alliance between the PNL, PD, the [[Conservative Party (Romania)|Conservative Party]] (PC) and the UDMR.<ref>{{cite book|editor1=Villy Tsakona|editor2=Diana Elena Popa|title=Studies in Political Humour: In Between Political Critique and Public Entertainment|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=uELvEqHybukC&pg=PA162|year=2011|publisher=John Benjamins Publishing|isbn=90-272-0637-6|page=162}}</ref> In April 2007, then PNL prime minister [[C\u0103lin Popescu-T\u0103riceanu]], who was also the party leader, formed a minority government solely with the UDMR and the remainder PD ministers were reshuffled. This cause internal opposition within the party and led to a splinter group, the [[Liberal Democratic Party (Romania)|Liberal Democratic Party]] (PLD), eventually merging with the PD to form the [[Democratic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]] (PDL).\n\nAfter the [[2008 Romanian legislative election|2008 legislative election]] the party placed third and entered official opposition, winning 19.74% seats in the Parliament, while the new grand coalition, formed by their former enlarged ally the democrat liberals (PDL) and the [[Social Democratic Party (Romania)|Social Democratic Party]] (PSD), had roughly 70%. At the [[2009 Romanian presidential election|2009 presidential election]] the National Liberal Party's then newly elected leader, [[Crin Antonescu]], finished third in the first round and the party still found itself in parliamentary opposition for the three next years to come.\n\n=== 2010\u20132020: New electoral alliances and third governing experiences ===\n\n[[File:Bucuresti, Romania, Aleea Modrogan nr. 1 (Vila); B-II-m-B-19227 (4).JPG|thumb|right|Central headquarters of the PNL located on Modrogan Alley, Bucharest]]\n\nOn 5 February 2011, the PNL formed the [[Social Liberal Union]] (USL) [[political alliance]] with the PSD, the [[National Union for the Progress of Romania]] (UNPR), and the [[Conservative Party (Romania)|Conservative Party]] (PC).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.cri.cn/6966/2011/02/06/1461s619327.htm |title=Romanian Oppositions Form Alliance |publisher=English.cri.cn |date= |accessdate=2011-11-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.focus-fen.net/index.php?id=n241429 |title=FOCUS Information Agency |publisher=Focus-fen.net |date= |accessdate=2011-11-13}}</ref> The PNL subsequently exited the USL on 25 February 2014, disbanding the alliance and returning to opposition.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sofiaglobe.com/2014/02/25/romanias-liberals-to-leave-ruling-coalition-government/ |title=Romania\u2019s Liberals to leave ruling coalition, government |publisher=The Sofia Globe |date= |accessdate=2014-07-16}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 May 2014, following the [[2014 European Parliament election in Romania|2014 European elections]], then PNL party president [[Crin Antonescu]] announced he was seeking membership within the [[European People's Party]] (EPP).<ref>{{cite web|author=EurActiv |url=http://www.euractiv.com/sections/eu-elections-2014/romanian-liberals-seek-epp-affiliation-302401 |title=Romanian liberals seek EPP affiliation |publisher=EurActiv |date=2014-05-26 |accessdate=2014-07-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://actmedia.eu/daily/antonescu-i-ll-have-talks-with-epp-in-june/52347 |title=Antonescu: I\u2019ll have talks with EPP in June |publisher=Actmedia.eu |date=2014-05-28 |accessdate=2014-07-16}}</ref> At the beginning of the [[Eighth European Parliament|8th European Parliament]], 5 of the PNL [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s sat with the [[European People's Party Group|EPP Group]],<ref>http://eppgroup.eu/party/Partidul-Na\u021bional-Liberal-(RO)</ref> and 1 with the [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe Group|ALDE Group]],<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.alde.eu/alde-group/alde-meps-list-member-european-parliament/alde-mep-details/personal-info/nicolai-norica/ |title=ALDE MEP details |publisher=Alde.eu |accessdate=2014-07-16 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140523170042/http://www.alde.eu/alde-group/alde-meps-list-member-european-parliament/alde-mep-details/personal-info/nicolai-norica/ |archive-date=23 May 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> who later became an independent MEP within ALDE.\n\nIn late May, 2014 the party agreed to a future merger with the Democratic Liberal Party (PDL), with the two parties main short-time goal being to submit a joint candidate for the upcoming presidential election.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.balkaneu.com/romanias-largest-rightist-parties-agree-presidential-candidate-fusion/ |title=Romania\u2019s largest rightist parties agree on presidential candidate, fusion &#124; Independent Balkan News Agency |publisher=Balkaneu.com |date=2014-05-29 |accessdate=2014-07-16}}</ref> The PNL-PDL presidential candidate was agreed to run under an [[electoral alliance|electoral banner]] called the [[Christian Liberal Alliance]] (ACL).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ziuanews.ro/politica/sigla-acl-a-intrat-de-luni-in-productie-128950|title=SIGLA ACL a intrat \u00een produc\u0163ie|work=ZIUAnews.ro|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ziarulunirea.ro/ion-dumitrel-florin-roman-adrian-teban-si-marius-ceteras-prim-vicepresedintii-aliantei-crestin-liberale-alba-acl-278175.html|title=Ion Dumitrel, Florin Roman, Adrian Teban \u0219i Marius Cetera\u0219,  prim-vicepre\u0219edin\u021bii Alian\u021bei Cre\u0219tin Liberale Alba (ACL)|work=Ziarul Unirea|accessdate=10 June 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141205043344/http://www.ziarulunirea.ro/ion-dumitrel-florin-roman-adrian-teban-si-marius-ceteras-prim-vicepresedintii-aliantei-crestin-liberale-alba-acl-278175.html|archive-date=5 December 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 27 June 2014, former PNL chairman [[C\u0103lin Popescu-T\u0103riceanu]] announced his intention to found a separate liberal party to run for president, stating opposition to the upcoming merger with the PDL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://business-review.eu/uncategorized/political-bombshell-calin-popescu-tariceanu-will-run-for-president-wants-to-start-new-liberal-party-66507|title=Calin Popescu Tariceanu will run for president|author=Newsroom|publisher=|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> The breakaway party, called the [[Liberal Reformist Party (Romania)|Liberal Reformist Party]] (PLR), was founded by Popescu-T\u0103riceanu on 3 July, 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://actmedia.eu/daily/tariceanu-the-liberal-reforming-party-is-advancing-liberalism/53023|title=Tariceanu: The Liberal Reforming Party is advancing Liberalism|author=ACTMedia - Romanian Business News|publisher=|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> On 17 July, 2014 it was announced that the future merger of the PNL and PDL would retain the National Liberal Party name, while being situated in the PDL's existing headquarters in Bucharest, and would be legally registered by the end of 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://actmedia.eu/daily/name-of-new-party-from-pdl-pnl-merger-is-pnl/53279 |title=Name of new party from PDL-PNL merger is PNL |publisher=Actmedia.eu |date= |accessdate=2014-07-19}}</ref> On 26 July 2014, a joint party congress of the PNL and PDL approved the merger.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.agerpres.ro/english/2014/07/26/merger-protocol-between-pnl-pdl-new-party-statute-approved-by-joint-congress-13-54-34|title=Merger protocol between PNL-PDL, new party statute, approved by joint congress|publisher=|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n[[File:PNL components.png|thumb|right|Diagram showcasing the political evolution of the National Liberal Party, from 1990 until 2016.]]\n\nIn the first round of the [[2014 Romanian presidential election|2014 presidential election]] on 2 November 2014, ACL presidential candidate [[Klaus Iohannis|Klaus Johannis]], PNL party president and Mayor of [[Sibiu]] ({{lang-de|Hermannstadt}}, [[Transylvanian Saxon dialect|Transylvanian Saxon]]: ''H\u00e4rmeschtat''), was the runner-up.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2014/11/03/us-romania-election-idUSKBN0IL3BN20141103|title=Romania's PM Ponta wins first round of presidential election|work=Reuters|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> Johannis won the runoff election held on 16 November 2014 with 54.5% of the total number of votes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-30076716|title=Romania election surprise as Klaus Iohannis wins presidency|work=BBC News|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thediplomat.ro/articol.php?id=5662|title=Romanians elected Klaus Iohannis their new president for the next five years|publisher=|accessdate=10 June 2015}}</ref> At the 2016 [[2016 Romanian local election|local elections]] and [[2016 Romanian local elections|legislative elections]], the PNL managed to finish second, behind the PSD, and consequently continuously in opposition since then.\n\nRegarding the [[2019 Romanian presidential election|2019 presidential election]], the party has formally announced its support for a second term of incumbent state president [[Klaus Iohannis|Klaus Johannis]] in March, 2018 along with an official designation of [[Ludovic Orban]], current party president, for the function of [[Prime Minister of Romania|Prime Minister]] should the PNL win the [[Next Romanian legislative election|2020 legislative elections]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Niculescu|first1=Anghel|title=Ludovic Orban a anun\u0163at pe cine va sus\u0163ine PNL la alegerile preziden\u0163iale din 2019! \u201eM\u0103 voi bate cu toat\u0103 for\u0163a mea s\u0103 ob\u0163inem un nou mandat pentru Klaus Iohannis\u201c|url=http://expressdebanat.ro/ludovic-orban-a-anuntat-pe-cine-va-sustine-pnl-la-alegerile-prezidentiale-din-2019-ma-voi-bate-cu-toata-forta-mea-sa-obtinem-un-nou-mandat-pentru-klaus-iohannis/|website=Express de Banat|accessdate=4 August 2017|language=Romanian}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://adevarul.ro/news/politica/conducerea-pnl-voteaza-sustinerea-presedintelui-iohannis-nou-mandat-orban-premier-1_5aa50844df52022f756ec670/index.html |title=Decizie PNL. Liberalii \u00eel sus\u0163in pe Klaus Iohannis pentru un nou mandat de pre\u015fedinte. Ludovic Orban - premierul PNL |work=Adev\u0103rul |author=Sebastian Zachmann |date=11 March 2018 |language=Romanian}}</ref> In June, 2018 at an open air press conference in his native Sibiu ({{lang-de|Hermannstadt}}, [[Transylvanian Saxon dialect|Transylvanian Saxon]]: ''H\u00e4rmeschtat''), Johannis publicly announced his intention to run for a second presidential term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digi24.ro/stiri/actualitate/politica/klaus-iohannis-a-anuntat-ca-va-candida-pentru-un-nou-mandat-de-presedinte-952012|title=Klaus Iohannis va candida pentru un nou mandat de pre\u0219edinte: \"Sunt ferm hot\u0103r\u00e2t\"|author=Digi24|work=www.digi24.ro|date=23 June 2018|accessdate=23 June 2018}}</ref> Furthermore, in 2019, the National Liberal Party acceded to governance under a minority stand-alone government which was voted twice by the Parliament.\n\n==Ideology==\n\nThe party adheres to the doctrine of [[liberalism]] in the form of [[conservative liberalism]] and [[national liberalism]], advocating both economic and social liberalization.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://pnl.ro/despre-noi/angajamentul-nostru/principii-si-valori-liberale | title=Partidul Na\u021bional Liberal, Despre Noi: Principii \u0219i valorile liberale | access-date=22 April 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180922121127/https://pnl.ro/despre-noi/angajamentul-nostru/principii-si-valori-liberale | archive-date=22 September 2018 | url-status=dead | df=dmy-all }}</ref> In recent years, it has focused more on [[economic liberalism]]. The National Liberal Party also supports conservative initiatives and policies and the state in moral and religious issues, as well as the [[privatization]] and denationalization of the economy, a trend which is currently taking place quite rapidly in Romania, as in other post-communist economies in [[Central and Eastern Europe]].\n\nIn economic regards, the National Liberal Party also deems significant the fact that [[tax]]es must be lowered and that the [[private sector]] of the national economy must be expanded and helped by a series of new laws in order to generate more value.<ref>{{cite web |  url=https://pnl.ro/despre-noi/angajamentul-nostru/programul-de-guvernare |  title=Partidul Na\u021bional Liberal, Angajamentul nostru: Programul de Guvernare al Partidului Na\u021bional Liberal |  access-date=22 April 2018 |  archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829212301/https://pnl.ro/despre-noi/angajamentul-nostru/programul-de-guvernare |  archive-date=29 August 2018 |  url-status=dead |  df=dmy-all }}</ref> It also advocates a decentralization of Romania's political structure, with greater autonomy given to the eight [[development regions of Romania|development regions]].\n\n== Structure ==\nAccording to the Statute, the leading organs of the party are the following:<ref>{{in lang|ro}} [http://www.pnl.ro/Public/art/3996/Structura-si-organizarea-Partidului-National-Liberal.html The structure of the Party] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090312073317/http://pnl.ro/Public/art/3996/Structura-si-organizarea-Partidului-National-Liberal.html |date=12 March 2009 }}</ref>\n\n=== Congress ===\nThe '''Congress''', or '''The General Assembly of the delegates of the party's members''' ({{lang-ro|Congresul; Adunarea General\u0103 a delega\u0163ilor membrilor partidului}}) is the supreme authority in the party. It leads the party and takes decisions at national level. Its members are elected by the local (territorial) organizations, and The National Consillium. The Congress meets every four years, after the parliamentary elections, or at any time needed. The Congress is convoked either by the Permanent Delegation (see below), at the request of the Central Political Bureau, or at the request of at least half of the Territorial Permanent Delegations. The Congress elects the President of the National Liberal Party, the 15 vice-presidents of the Central Standing Bureau (7 with specific attributions and 8 responsible for the [[Development regions of Romania|development regions]], 23 judges of The Honor and Referee Court ({{lang-ro|Curtea de Onoare \u015fi Arbitraj}}), 7 members of The Central Committee of Censors ({{lang-ro|Comisia Central\u0103 de Cenzori}}).\n\nThe last Congress took place between 5\u20136 March 2010, as both an Extraordinary and Ordinary Congress. The Extraordinary Congress took place on 5 March, because it was called three months earlier than the scheduled Ordinary Congress. It changed the Statute of the party. On 6 March the Congress was Ordinary, based on the new Statute.\n\n=== Permanent Delegation ===\nThe '''Permanent Delegation''' ({{lang-ro|Delega\u0163ia Permanent\u0103}} \u2013 DP) is the structure that leads the party between two Congresses. It meets monthly, or at any time needed. Its members are the following; the President of the National Liberal Party, the members of the Central Political Bureau, the President of the Senate of the party, the Secretary General of the National Liberal Party, the presidents of the two [[Parliament of Romania|Chambers of the Parliament]] (if the officeholders are members of the PNL), the leaders of the National liberal Party's parliamentary groups, the Senators and Deputies, the MEPs, the Ministers, the President of the [[National Liberal Youth (Romania)|National Liberal Youth]] (TNL), the President of the [[Liberal Women Organisation (Romania)|Liberal Women Organisation]] (OFL), the President of the [[Liberal Student Clubs (Romania)|Liberal Student Clubs]] (CSL), the President of the League of the Local Elected Officeholders of the National Liberal Party (LAL PNL), the President of the Coordinating Council of the Municipality of Bucharest, the [[European Commissioner]] (if the officeholder is member of the PNL).\n\n=== National Political Bureau ===\nThe '''National Political Bureau''' ({{lang-ro|Biroul Politic Na\u021bional}} \u2013 BPN) of the National Liberal Party proposes the party's politics and coordinates its application. It ensures the party's day-to-day leadership, and it is composed by the following: the President of the party, the 15 Vice-Presidents (7 with specific charges, and 8 responsible for the development regions). At the BPC's meetings can assist, with consultative vote, the president of the Senate of the PNL, the Secretary-General of the PNL, the Presidents of the two [[Parliament of Romania|Chambers of the Parliament]] (if the officeholders are members of the PNL), the leaders of the National liberal Party's parliamentary groups, the President of the TNL, the President of the OFL, the President of the CSL, the President of the League of the LAL, and the Ministers. The BPC meets weekley, or at any time needed, convoked by the president of the PNL.\n\nAccording to Article 70 of the PNL Statute, the BPN coordinates and evaluates the objectives of the territorial branches, of the parliamentary groups; it negotiates political agreements (within the limits established by the DP); it coordinates the elections campaign; proposes sanctions according to the Statute; proposes to the DP the political strategy of the party; proposes the candidates for the central executive or public offices; for certain territorial units, proposes to the DP the candidates for the parliamentary elections; proposes to the DP the candidates for the [[European Parliament elections]]; proposes the DP to dissolve or dismiss, for exceptional reasons, the territorial branch, or the branch's president; convokes the DP; coordinates the activity of the permanent committees of the National Council, validates or invalidates the results of the elections for the territorial branches; appoints the Secretary-Executive, the Foreign Secretary, and Deputy-Secretaries-General.\n\nThe BPN is assisted, in the organizing activity by the Secretary General of the PNL. This office ensures the communication between the central organisms and the territorial branches, ensures the management of the party's assets, is responsible for the informational system. The Secretary-General is assisted by the Deputy-Secretaries-General, appointed by the BPC at the suggestion of the Secretary-General.\n\nAs of 2018, the National Political Bureau is composed of the following members:<ref>{{cite web |url=https://pnl.ro/reprezentanti/birou-executiv-pnl |title=Biroul Executiv al PNL |publisher=PNL |accessdate=22 April 2018 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n* President: [[Ludovic Orban]]\n* Secretary General: Robert Sighiart\u0103u\n* Vice-Presidents: Ilie Bolojan, [[Raluca Turcan]], Iulian Dumitrescu, Mircea Hava, Vlad Nistor, Lauren\u021biu Leoreanu, Ben-Oni Ardelean, Florin C\u00ee\u0163u, Dan Motreanu, Adrian Oros, Virgil Guran, Ioan B\u0103lan, Victor Paul Dobre, R\u0103ducu Filipescu, Gigel \u0218tirbu, [[Gheorghe Falc\u0103]], Lucian Bode, Florin Roman, Marian Petrache, [[Cristian Bu\u0219oi]]\n* Leader of the PNL Parliamentary Group in the [[Senate of Romania|Senate]]: Iulian Dumitrescu\n* Leader of the PNL Parliamentary Group in the [[Chamber of Deputies of Romania|Chamber of Deputies]]: [[Raluca Turcan]]\n\nIn normal conditions, the term of the BPN members ends during the Party's Congress, when the president leaves the presidium of the Congress. The president of the Standing Bureau of the Congress is, formally, the acting president of the party until the new president is elected. The last acting president of the National Liberal Party was [[Mircea Ionescu-Quintus]] on 20 March 2009, when [[Crin Antonescu]] succeeded [[C\u0103lin Popescu-T\u0103riceanu]].\n\n=== National Council ===\nThe '''National Council''' ({{lang-ro|Consiliul Na\u0163ional \u2013 CN}}) is the debate forum of the National Liberal Party between two Congresses. It reunites twice a year, or at any time necessary, convoked by the president, by the BPC, or at the request of at least half of its members. Its members are: DP, including the members with consultative vote; the Secretaries of State and the equivalent officeholders; the [[Prefect]]s and Deputy-Prefects; Presidents and Vice-Presidents of the [[Counties of Romania|County]] Councils; Mayors and Deputy-Mayors of the county capitals, of the [[sectors of Bucharest]], the General Mayor and General Deputy-Mayors of [[Bucharest]]; the Vice-Presidents and Secretaries-General of TNL, OFL, CSL, the Senate of the Party, LAL; honorary members of the party; the President of the structures that deal with specific issues; the Presidents of the CN.\n\nThe CN has the following competences: acts to fulfill the decisions of the Congress; adopts the Governing Program; adopts the programs and sectorial politics of the party; approves the reports of the specialty committees; names the candidate of the National Liberal Party for the [[President of Romania|Romanian Presidency]]; gives and retracts the quality of honorary member of the party.\n\nAccording to Article 65 of the Statute, the CN is organized and functions through its permanent specialty committees, constituted on social and professional criteria. The committees constituted on social criteria promote the interests of the correspondent social category. The committees constituted on professional criteria state the sectorial politics and the public politics in major fields, to express the options and solutions proposed by the National Liberal Party.\n\n=== President ===\nThe '''President of the National Liberal Party''' is the guardian of the political Program of the party, of the respect to the Statute and the keeping of the unity and prestige of the party.\n\n=== Secretary-General ===\nThe '''Secretary-General''' ensures the communication between the central leading structures and the territorial ones, ensures the management of the assets of the party, is responsible for the informational system. The Secretary-General is helped in its activity by Deputy-Secretaries-General appointed by the BPC, upon the suggestion of the Secretary-General.\n\n=== Other national structures ===\n\n* The Senate of the party \u2013 consulting organism for the president regarding the continuity and development of the liberal traditions and concepts;\n* Court of Honor and Arbitration \u2013 the supreme court of the party;\n* Central Committee of Censors \u2013 checks the management of the party;\n* Ethics Commission \u2013 analyzes the candidates proposed for the [[Elections in Romania|legislative elections]] and for the offices in the [[Government of Romania|Government]] as well as other central offices;\n* [[National Liberal Youth (Romania)|National Liberal Youth]] \u2013 coordinates the activity specific to the youth structures in the territory;\n* League of the Local Elected Officeholders \u2013 coordinates the activity of the PNL members in the local public administration (mayors and deputy-mayors, local councilors, county councilors, county council presidents, and deputy-presidents);\n* [[Liberal Women Organisation (Romania)|Liberal Women Organisation]] \u2013 coordinates the activity of the territorial women organizations;\n* [[Liberal Student Clubs (Romania)|Liberal Student Clubs]] \u2013 promotes the liberal ideas and political program of the PNL through the students.\n\n=== Local leading structures ===\nThe local leading structures of the National Liberal Party are the following:\n\n* the '''General Assembly of the Members''' ({{lang-ro|Adunarea General\u0103 a membrilor \u2013 AG}}) \u2013 applies at local level the necessary measures for fulfilling the Program and Strategy.\n* the '''Standing Bureau of the organization''' ({{lang-ro|Biroul Permanent \u2013 BP}}) \u2013 leads the organization between two General Assemblies.\n\n== Symbol ==\n\nRomanian law requires all parties to present a permanent sign and a permanent electoral sign. The former is used to identify the party's buildings and press releases, and the latter to identify the party's electoral materials and the candidates on the elections ballot. Usually they differ slightly.\n\nThe main element of the party is a blue arrow pointing to the upper right corner of a yellow square, and the letters ''P'', ''N'', and ''L'' in blue, tilted to the right. The position of the ''PNL'' with respect to the arrow depends on the type of symbol, as shown below.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nFile:National Liberal Party Romania.png|Current PNL logo and electoral sign (in use 2014\u2013present)\nFile:Sigla PNL.jpg|The former electoral sign (used prior to 2014)\nImage:Sigla_pnl.png|Former permanent sign (used prior to 2014)\n</gallery>\n\n== Party leaders ==\n<div style=\"text-align:right; float:right; margin-left:5px\">{{National Liberal Party leadership timeline}}</div>\n\n{{legend|#00BFFF|Also served as state vice president in the Provisional National Unity Council ({{lang-ro|Consiliul Provizoriu de Uniune Na\u021bional\u0103}})|outline=silver}}\n{{legend|#87CEEB|Also served as ''ad interim'' (i.e. [[Acting (law)|acting]]) [[President of Romania]]|outline=silver}}\n{{legend|#1E90FF|Also served as [[President of Romania]]|outline=silver}}\n{{legend|#FFFF00|Also served as [[Prime Minister of Romania|Prime Minister]]|outline=silver}}\n{{legend|#FFD700|Also served as [[Senate of Romania|Senate]] [[President of the Senate of Romania|President]]|outline=silver}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| N\u00ba\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Name<br>{{small|Born - Died}}\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Portrait\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Term start\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Term end\n! style=\"background:#ccc;\"| Duration\n|- style=\"background:#00BFFF\"\n! 1\n| [[Radu C\u00e2mpeanu]]<br>{{small|(1922\u20132016)}}\n| [[File:Radu C\u00e2mpeanu.jpg|60px]]\n| 15 January 1990\n| 28 February 1993\n| {{nowrap|{{age in years, months and days|1990|1|15|1993|2|28}}}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFD700\"\n! 2\n| [[Mircea Ionescu Quintus]]<br>{{small|(1917\u20132017)}}\n| \n| 28 February 1993\n| 18 February 2001\n| {{nowrap|{{age in years, months and days|1993|2|28|2001|2|18}}}}\n|-\n! 3\n| [[Valeriu Stoica]]<br>{{small|(1953\u2013 }}\n| [[File:Valeriu Stoica(cropped).JPG|60px]]\n| 18 February 2001\n| 24 August 2002\n| {{nowrap|{{age in years, months and days|2001|2|18|2002|8|24}}}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF00\"\n! 4\n| [[Theodor Stolojan]]<br>{{small|(1943\u2013 }}\n| [[File:Conventia PD-L 2013 - Theodor Stolojan (2).jpg|60px]]\n| 24 August 2002\n| 2 October 2004\n| {{nowrap|{{age in years, months and days|2002|8|24|2004|10|2}}}}\n|- style=\"background:#FFFF00\"\n! 5\n| [[C\u0103lin Popescu-T\u0103riceanu]]<br>{{small|(1952\u2013 }}\n| [[File:Victor Ponta la semnarea declaratiei politice privind infiintarea USL 2.0 - 14.11 (4) (15621866127) (cropped 2).jpg|60px]]\n| 2 October 2004\n| 20 March 2009\n| {{nowrap|{{age in years, months and days|2004|10|2|2009|3|20}}}}\n|- style=\"back