atic Liberal Party (Romania)|Democratic Liberal Party]] (PDL).</small>\n<br>\n\n=== European elections ===\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align: right;\" width=70%\n|-\n! Election !! Votes !! Percentage !! [[Member of the European Parliament|MEP]]s !! Position !! Political group\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[2007 European Parliament election in Romania|2007]]\n| 688,859\n| 13.4% {{steady}}\n| {{Composition bar|6|35|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{color box|#CD7F32|3rd}}\n| [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe group|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] (ALDE)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[2009 European Parliament election in Romania|2009]]\n| 702,974\n| 14.5% {{increase}}\n| {{Composition bar|5|33|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{color box|#CD7F32|3rd}}\n| [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe group|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] (ALDE)\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[2014 European Parliament election in Romania|2014]]\n| 835,531\n| 15.0% {{increase}}\n| {{Composition bar|6|32|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{color box|Silver|2nd}}\n| [[Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe group|Alliance of Liberals and Democrats for Europe]] (ALDE)<sup>1</sup>\n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! [[2019 European Parliament election in Romania|2019]]\n| 2,449,068\n| 27.0% {{increase}}\n| {{Composition bar|10|32|hex={{National Liberal Party (Romania)/meta/color}}}}\n| {{color box|Gold|1st}}\n| [[European People's Party group|European People's Party]] (EPP)\n|}\n\n'''Notes''':\n\n<sup>1</sup> <small>Subsequently sought permission to adhere to the [[European People's Party group|European People's Party]] (EPP)</small>.\n\n== See also ==\n* [[National Liberal Party (Moldova)|National Liberal Party (Republic of Moldova)]]\n* [[Liberalism and radicalism in Romania]]\n* [[List of political parties in Romania]]\n* [[Liberalism by country|List of liberal parties]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120906010541/http://www.pnl.ro/pagina/presedintii-pnl PNL website retrieved 8 September 2012]\n* Cliveti, Gheorghe, Liberalismul rom\u00e2nesc. Eseu istoriografic, Editura Funda\u021biei \"AXIS\", Ia\u0219i, 1996;\n* Istoricul PNL de la 1848 p\u00e2n\u0103 ast\u0103zi, Bucure\u0219ti, 1923;\n* R\u0103dulescu \u2013 Zoner, \u0218erban (coord.), Cliveti, Gheorghe, Stan, Apostol, Oni\u015foru, Gheorghe, \u0218andru, Dumitru, Istoria Partidului Na\u021bional Liberal, Editura All, Bucure\u0219ti, 2000;\n* Stan, Apostol, Iosa, Mircea, Liberalismul politic \u00een Rom\u00e2nia. De la origini p\u00e2n\u0103 la 1918, Editura Enciclopedic\u0103, Bucure\u0219ti, 1996;\n* Naumescu, Valentin, Despre liberalism \u00een Rom\u00e2nia. Realit\u0103\u0163i, dileme, perspective, EFES, Cluj-Napoca, 2001;\n* \u0218omlea, Vasile-Florin, Mi\u0219carea liberal\u0103 din Rom\u00e2nia post'1989, Editura Ecumenica Press, Cluj-Napoca, 2006;\n\n==External links==\n*[https://pnl.ro/ Official website]  {{in lang|ro}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20070329184556/http://www.lal-pnl.ro/ League of the Local Representatives of the National Liberal Party official site]\n{{European People's Party}}\n{{Romanian political parties}}\n{{PNLHeads}}\n\n[[Category:National Liberal Party (Romania)| ]]\n[[Category:Conservative parties in Romania]]\n[[Category:Liberal parties in Romania]]\n", "name_user": "Rosenborg BK Fan", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor sourcing edit in the introduction", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/National_Liberal_Party_(Romania)"}
{"title_page": "2015 in Singapore", "text_new": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2015}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during [[2015]] '''in the [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[Tony Tan Keng Yam]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Lee Hsien Loong]]\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n*1 January - The [[National Youth Council Singapore|National Youth Council]] becomes an autonomous agency since being formed as a [[People's Association]] division in 1989.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/national-youth-council-be-autonomous-agency-under-mccy-jan-1 |title=National Youth Council to be autonomous agency under MCCY from Jan 1 |website=Asiaone |date=29 December 2014 |accessdate=4 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704004416/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/national-youth-council-be-autonomous-agency-under-mccy-jan-1 |archive-date=4 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*3 January - The Singaporean car carrier ''[[Hoegh Osaka]]'' runs aground on Bramble Bank of the [[Isle of Wight]], in the entrance to [[Southampton Water]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-hampshire-30670746 | title=Crew rescued from listing Solent car transporter | publisher=BBC News | date=3 January 2015 | accessdate=4 January 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104030807/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-hampshire-30670746 | archive-date=4 January 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*14 January - [https://web.archive.org/web/20150114110705/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/train-commuters-face/1589068.html First SMRT train service disruption] east-bound train travelling from Joo Koon to Dover.\n*23 January - JTC LaunchPad @ one-north is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening of JTC LaunchPad @ one-north |url=https://www.jtc.gov.sg/news-and-publications/speeches/Pages/20150123(SPb).aspx |publisher=JTC Corporation |accessdate=3 August 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218205004/https://www.jtc.gov.sg/news-and-publications/speeches/Pages/20150123(SPb).aspx |archivedate=18 December 2015 |date=23 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*29 January - The [[Liquor Control (Supply and Consumption) Act 2015|Liquor Control (Supply and Consumption) Act]] was passed in Parliament. The law bans drinking in public from 10:30pm to 7am and designated Liquor Control Zones, which took effect on 1 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/what-you-can-or-cannot-do-under-the-new-alcohol-law|title=What You Can or Cannot do under the new Alcohol Law|publisher=Straits Times|date=1 April 2015|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708221316/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/what-you-can-or-cannot-do-under-the-new-alcohol-law|archive-date=8 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/stricter-alcohol-laws-passed-expected-take-effect-april|title=Stricter alcohol laws passed, expected to take effect in April|publisher=Todayonline|date=29 January 2015|accessdate=6 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606011118/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/stricter-alcohol-laws-passed-expected-take-effect-april|archive-date=6 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*11 February - [[Blk71|BASH]] is launched for [[startups]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=Ann |title=BASH is launched: Biggest facility yet to help grow startups in Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/bash-is-launched-biggest-facility-yet-to-help-grow-startups-in-singapore |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=20 August 2019 |date=11 February 2015}}</ref>\n*16 February - [[JTC Corporation]] and [[Temasek Holdings]] have agreed to merge their subsidiaries to better compete in Asia, first announced on 4 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Weizhen |title=Temasek, JTC to merge 4 units into mega-entity |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/temasek-jtc-merge-4-units-mega-entity |website=Today |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=5 September 2014}}</ref> The mergers will involve Ascendas and Singbridge, as well as Surbana and Jurong International Holdings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/temasek-jtc-give-official-blessing-to-merger-of-subsidiaries |title=Temasek, JTC give official blessing to merger of subsidiaries |website=The Straits Times |date=16 February 2015 |accessdate=1 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701180022/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/temasek-jtc-give-official-blessing-to-merger-of-subsidiaries |archive-date=1 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The merger is completed on 10 June, resulting in the formation of [[Ascendas-Singbridge]] (since acquired by [[CapitaLand]]) and [[Surbana Jurong]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ascendas and Singbridge Complete Merger |url=https://www.ascendas-singbridge.com/-/media/ascendas/files/press-release/press-release-2015/20150610-newsrelease-ascendas-and-singbridge-complete-merger.ashx |website=Ascendas-Singbridge |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=10 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Merger between Surbana International and Jurong International completed |url=https://surbanajurong.com/resources/press-releases/merger-surbana-international-jurong-international-completed/ |website=Surbana Jurong |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=10 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n*March - [[Capitol Piazza]] is opened to the public as part of [[Capitol Building, Singapore|Capitol]].\n*10 March - A memorial was launched to commemorate the [[MacDonald House bombing]] that happened 50 years earlier.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lim |first1=Yan Liang |title=Memorial to victims of Konfrontasi unveiled near MacDonald House |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/memorial-to-victims-of-konfrontasi-unveiled-near-macdonald-house |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=23 July 2019 |date=10 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723154859/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/memorial-to-victims-of-konfrontasi-unveiled-near-macdonald-house |archive-date=23 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*11 March - Innosparks (an [[ST Engineering]] subsidiary) launches the AIR+ Smart Mask, which consists of a Smart Mask and the AIR+; a micro ventilator. This will help keep those wearing the mask cool, while giving protection from the haze and pollutants. It is able to fit people of all ages including children and the elderly.<ref>{{cite web |title=ST Engineering's Subsidiary Develops The AIR+ Smart Mask, Brings A New Approach To Protective Mask Technology |url=https://www.stengg.com/en/newsroom/news-releases/st-engineering-subsidiary-develops-the-airplus-smart-mask-brings-a-new-approach-to-protective-mask-technology/ |publisher=ST Engineering |accessdate=20 August 2019 |date=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n*13 March - Laws were passed to clarify that landowners can use up to 30 m underground below the Singapore Height Datum, and allow for acquisition of underground space.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Yvonne |title=Proposed law will allow Govt to acquire specific stratum of underground space |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/proposed-law-will-allow-govt-acquire-specific-stratum-underground-space |accessdate=20 July 2019 |publisher=Todayonline |date=12 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720161901/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/proposed-law-will-allow-govt-acquire-specific-stratum-underground-space |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Second Reading Speech by Senior Minister of State for Law, Indranee Rajah SC, on the State Lands (Amendment) Bill 2015 |url=https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/parliamentary-speeches-and-responses/2R-state-lands-amendment-bill-2015.html |publisher=MinLaw |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=13 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720161858/https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/parliamentary-speeches-and-responses/2R-state-lands-amendment-bill-2015.html |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Second Reading Speech by Senior Minister of State for Law, Indranee Rajah SC, on the Land Acquisition (Amendment) Bill 2015 |url=https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/parliamentary-speeches-and-responses/2R-land-acquisition-amendment-bill-2015.html |publisher=MinLaw |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=13 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720161911/https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/parliamentary-speeches-and-responses/2R-land-acquisition-amendment-bill-2015.html |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*16 March - [[Eng Wah Global|WE Cinemas]] opens a new multiplex in 321 Clementi, which also opened on the same day. This marked WE Cinemas' re-entry into the cinema business.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lui |first1=John |title=Eng Wah Clementi cineplex opens, marks operator WE Cinemas' return after two years |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/eng-wah-clementi-cineplex-opens-marks-operator-we-cinemas-return-after-two |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=16 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814154122/https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/eng-wah-clementi-cineplex-opens-marks-operator-we-cinemas-return-after-two |archive-date=14 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*23-29 March - [[Death of Lee Kuan Yew]]:\n**23 March -\n***Singapore's first and former [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Kuan Yew]], notable for his contributions as an \"Architect of Modern Singapore\", passes on at age of 91 at 3:18 am in [[Singapore General Hospital]] due to complications of [[pneumonia]]. \n***Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] (who was also the son of the late Lee) declared a seven-day period of national mourning and the funeral will be held on March 29. The state flags on all government buildings would be flown at half-mast for the mourning period, while a majority of television programmings were pre-empted to air a selected series of programs in tribute of Lee.\n**25 March - \n***The funeral procession of Lee from the [[Istana Singapore|Istana]] to [[Parliament House, Singapore|Parliament House]] to lay in state. Later on the same day, the house was opened to Singapore who queued to pay their last respects to Lee.\n**29 March - \n***The funeral procession of Lee from the [[Parliament House, Singapore|Parliament House]] to [[National University of Singapore]] (NUS) University Cultural Centre.\n***Lee's body was cremated and interred at [[Mandai Crematorium and Columbarium]].\n* 29 March - [[Amos Yee]] was arrested for insensitive remarks. He was charged and found guilty, with a jail term imposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/amos-yee-who-made-insensitive-remarks-on-christianity-in-video-arrested|title=Amos Yee, who made insensitive remarks on Christianity in video, arrested|date=2015-03-30|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704041430/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/amos-yee-who-made-insensitive-remarks-on-christianity-in-video-arrested|archive-date=2019-07-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April - \n**[[xinmsn]] ceased operation and its services was transferred to [[MSN]] Singapore and [[Toggle (website)|Toggle]].\n**The [[Cyber Security Agency (Singapore)|Cyber Security Agency]] is formed under the [[Prime Minister's Office (Singapore)|Prime Minister's Office]] to oversee [[cybersecurity]] matters, taking over the Singapore Infocomm Technology Security Authority and the Singapore Computer Emergency Response Team. The agency is first announced on 27 January.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Irene |title=New Cyber Security Agency to be set up in April, Yaacob Ibrahim to be minister in charge of cyber security |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-cyber-security-agency-to-be-set-up-in-april-yaacob-ibrahim-to-be-minister-in-charge-of |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=26 September 2019 |date=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n*8 April - The [[Puss in Boots' Giant Journey]] ride opens in [[Universal Studios Singapore]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee Miller |first1=Shawn |title=New Puss In Boots ride at Universal Studios Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/new-puss-in-boots-ride-at-universal-studios-singapore |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=8 April 2015}}</ref>\n*30 April - Genting Hotel in Jurong was opened, making it the first hotel in west Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Genting Hotel in Jurong to open on Apr 30 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-genting-hotel-in-jurong-to-open-on-apr-30 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707081623/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-genting-hotel-in-jurong-to-open-on-apr-30 |archive-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |date=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 1 May - Fast food chain [[Wendy's]] closes its last outlet in [[National University of Singapore]].\n* 5 May - [[Jurong East]] was chosen as the [[Singapore]] terminus of the [[Kuala Lumpur\u2013Singapore High Speed Rail]], resulting in Jurong Country Club's acquisition on 11 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/high-speed-rail-terminus-be-located-jurong-east |title=High Speed Rail terminus to be located in Jurong East |publisher=Todayonline |date=5 May 2015 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804104629/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/high-speed-rail-terminus-be-located-jurong-east |archive-date=4 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/jurong-country-club-make-way-hsr |title=Jurong Country Club to make way for HSR |publisher=Todayonline |date=11 May 2015 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804104631/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/jurong-country-club-make-way-hsr |archive-date=4 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 11 May - New laws to regulate the use of drones are passed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-new-law-passed-to-regulate-the-use-of-drones | title=Parliament: New law passed to regulate the use of drones | publisher=The Straits Times | date=11 May 2015 | accessdate=1 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701180022/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-new-law-passed-to-regulate-the-use-of-drones | archive-date=1 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The laws, also known as the Unmanned Aircraft (Public Safety and Security) Act, have come into force on 1 June.\n* 15 May - [[Singapore Botanical Gardens]] gets [[ICOMOS]] nod to be the first [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]].\n* 19 May - [[Capitol Theatre, Singapore|Capitol Theatre]] was reopened as part of [[Capitol Building, Singapore|Capitol]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/capitol-theatre-to-re-open-10-things-about-the-new-capitol-singapore | title=Capitol Theatre to re-open: 10 things about the new Capitol Singapore | publisher=The Straits Times | date=11 May 2015 | accessdate=11 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711052007/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/capitol-theatre-to-re-open-10-things-about-the-new-capitol-singapore | archive-date=11 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 21 May - Construction starts on [[Outram Community Hospital]], which will be completed by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheong |first1=Kash |title=New Outram Community Hospital to ease crunch with additional 550 beds |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/new-outram-community-hospital-to-ease-crunch-with-additional-550-beds |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=21 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708161114/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/new-outram-community-hospital-to-ease-crunch-with-additional-550-beds |archive-date=8 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 23 May - [[LionsXII]] wins the Malaysian FA Cup for the first time after beating Kelantan, 3-1 in the final at the National Stadium, Bukit Jalil.\n* 27 May - [[Battlestar Galactica (roller coaster)|Battlestar Galactica]] reopens in [[Universal Studios Singapore]] after a two-year closure with new two-seater vehicles.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wee |first1=Cheryl Faith |title=Universal Studios Singapore's main attraction Battlestar Galactica reopens |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/universal-studios-singapores-main-attraction-battlestar-galactica-reopens |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n* 29 May - The [[National Arts Council, Singapore|National Arts Council]] (NAC) withdraws funding for [[The Art of Charlie Chan Hock Chye]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/national-arts-council-revokes-grant-for-graphic-novel-Sonny-Liew |title=NAC withdraws grant for graphic novel publisher due to \u201csensitive content\u201d |website=Today |date=29 May 2015 |access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> On 3 June, the NAC added that the book could undermine legitimacy of the [[Singapore government]], thus going against NAC funding rules.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yong |first1=Charissa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/nac-pulled-grant-from-comic-as-it-potentially-undermines-the-authority-of-the-government |title=NAC pulled grant from comic as it 'potentially undermines the authority of the Government' |website=The Straits Times |date=3 June 2015 |access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 31 May - A [[Shooting of Taufik Zahar|police shooting]] took place when a suspect attempted to escape from a police stop, killing one. Two other suspects were arrested and sentenced for drug offences.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/sporean-man-shot-dead-by-police-2-others-detained-in-incident-near-shangri-la | title=S'porean man shot dead by police, 2 others detained in incident near Shangri-La Hotel | publisher=The Straits Times | date=31 May 2015 | accessdate=3 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025140/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/sporean-man-shot-dead-by-police-2-others-detained-in-incident-near-shangri-la | archive-date=3 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/accused-shangri-la-shooting-sentenced | title=Accused in Shangri-La shooting sentenced | publisher=Todayonline | date=21 December 2015 | accessdate=3 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025143/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/accused-shangri-la-shooting-sentenced | archive-date=3 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===June===\n*5\u201316 June - [[2015 Southeast Asian Games]] was held in Singapore.\n*5 June - [[2015 Sabah earthquake]]: At least nine people, mostly from [[Tanjong Katong Primary School]] (TKPS) were killed when an earthquake measuring 6.0 on Richter scale struck [[Mount Kinabalu]] and [[Ranau]] in the state of [[Sabah]], [[Malaysia]]. A National mourning happened for the victims on 8 June, and [[half-mast]] were flown. As of 10 June, 11 victims were reported after two more were found on Kinabalu.\n*15 June - The [[Infocomm Development Authority of Singapore|Infocomm Development Authority]] allows all telcos to shut 2G services from 1 April 2017 to free up capacity for newer 4G services, as well as low subscribership.<ref>{{cite web |title=MNOs to close 2G networks from 1 April 2017 |url=https://www.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/ida/Media-Releases/2015/mnos-to-close-2g-networks-from-1-april-2017 |website=IDA (now IMDA) |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=15 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Irene |title=Singapore pulls plug on 2G mobile networks, to reuse airwaves for newer 4G services |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-pulls-plug-on-2g-mobile-networks-to-reuse-airwaves-for-newer-4g-services |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n*20 June - A police officer was shot by a suspect in [[Khoo Teck Puat Hospital]]. The suspect was sentenced to life with caning in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/police-officer-shot-duty-khoo-teck-puat-hospital |title=Police officer shot at Khoo Teck Puat Hospital |publisher=Todayonline |date=20 June 2015 |accessdate=3 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025145/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/police-officer-shot-duty-khoo-teck-puat-hospital |archive-date=3 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-shot-police-officer-gets-life-term-in-jail-caning |title=Man who snatched police officer's revolver and fired three shots gets life term in jail, caning |publisher=The Straits Times |date=20 March 2015 |accessdate=3 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025407/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-shot-police-officer-gets-life-term-in-jail-caning |archive-date=3 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 22 June - [[Surbana Jurong]] is launched, along with the announcement of several acquisitions to boost its regional standing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Surbana Jurong Private Limited launched, makes two acquisitions in Singapore & China |url=https://surbanajurong.com/resources/press-releases/surbana-jurong-private-limited-launched-makes-two-acquisitions-singapore-china/ |website=Surbana Jurong |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n* 23 June - The third satellite blood collection centre opens in Jurong East.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hsa.gov.sg/content/hsa/en/News_Events/Press_Releases/2015/hsa-opens-third-satellitebloodbankinjurongeast.html|title=HSA Opens Third Satellite Blood Bank in Jurong East|publisher=HSA|date=23 June 2015|accessdate=12 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712101322/https://www.hsa.gov.sg/content/hsa/en/News_Events/Press_Releases/2015/hsa-opens-third-satellitebloodbankinjurongeast.html|archive-date=12 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mof.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/Speech-by-Mr-Tharman-Shanmugaratnam-Deputy-Prime-Minister-and-Minister-for-Finance-at-the-Opening-of-the-Bloodbank@Westgate-Tower|title=Opening of the Bloodbank@Westgate Tower|publisher=MOF|date=23 June 2015|accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 26 June - The first [[Alstom Metropolis C830C|C830C]] train begins operations on the [[Circle MRT line]].\n* 27 June - [[Kupang LRT station]] is opened for service, along with more trips added, completing the [[Sengkang LRT line]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2015-06-15-02.aspx |title=Kupang LRT Station to Open and More than 260 Weekly Trips to be Added to the Sengkang/Punggol LRT |publisher=SBS Transit |access-date=29 August 2019 |date=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n* 30 June - The [[Ng Teng Fong General Hospital]] is opened, along with [[Jurong Community Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lynette |first1=Tan |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/ng-teng-fong-general-hospital-finally-ready-serve-patients |title=Ng Teng Fong General Hospital finally ready to serve patients |website=Today |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=1 July 2015}}</ref> The hospitals are officially opened on 10 October 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-opening-ng-teng-fong-general-hospital-jurong |title=Opening of Ng Teng Fong General Hospital & Jurong Community Hospital |website=PMO |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=11 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/more-hospitals-needed-patient-numbers-due-aging-population-pm-lee |title=As healthcare needs grow, S'pore must continue to get the system right: PM Lee |website=Today |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n*3 July - The first [[Independence-class littoral mission vessel|littoral mission vessel]] (LMV) is launched, going fully operational in 2017. The ships, which were designed and built locally, will have 8 ships when fully commissioned.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore launches first of eight new warships that are designed, built locally|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/singapore-launches-first-of-eight-new-warships-that-are-designed-built-locally|publisher=The Straits Times|date=3 July 2015|accessdate=17 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617144412/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/singapore-launches-first-of-eight-new-warships-that-are-designed-built-locally|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore's first Littoral Mission Vessel RSS Independence now fully operational|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-first-littoral-mission-vessel-rss-independence-now-fully-operational|publisher=The Straits Times|date=5 May 2017|accessdate=17 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617144409/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-first-littoral-mission-vessel-rss-independence-now-fully-operational|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*4 July - The 156-year-old [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]] became the first site to receive the status of [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zaccheus |first1=Melody |title=Singapore Botanic Gardens clinches prestigious Unesco World Heritage site status |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-botanic-gardens-clinches-prestigious-unesco-world-heritage-site-status |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=4 July 2015}}</ref>  \n*7 July - The [[North South MRT line|North South]] and [[East West MRT line|East West]] lines are disrupted due to a power fault, making it one of the worst MRT disruptions since 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=MRT breakdown: North-South, East-West lines down for hours |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/train-services-down-north-south-and-east-west-lines |publisher=Today |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n*13 July - \n**[[2015 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]: The [[List of Singaporean electoral divisions|Electoral Boundaries Review Committee]] is announced in [[Parliament of Singapore|Parliament]], having been formed two months ago.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Fang |first1=Joy |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/electoral-boundaries-review-committee-formed-pm |title=Electoral boundaries panel tasked to look into having smaller GRCs |website=Today |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=13 July 2015}}</ref>\n**Amendments to the [[Constitution of Singapore|Constitution]] were passed to include [[Temasek Holdings|Temasek]] into the Net Investment Returns framework from 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tham |first=Yuen-C |title=Parliament: Bill introduced to include more of Temasek's contributions in Govt revenue |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-bill-introduced-to-include-more-of-temaseks-contributions-in-govt-revenue |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=11 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720164206/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-bill-introduced-to-include-more-of-temaseks-contributions-in-govt-revenue |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Second Reading Speech by Mr Tharman Shanmugaratnam, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Finance, for the Constitution of the Republic of Singapore (Amendment) Bill 2015 at the Parliament, 13 Jul 2015 |url=https://www.mof.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/Second-Reading-Speech-by-Mr-Tharman-Shanmugaratnam-Deputy-Prime-Minister-and-Minister-for-Finance-for-the-Constitution-of-the-Republic-of-Singapore-(A |publisher=MOF |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=13 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720164214/https://www.mof.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/Second-Reading-Speech-by-Mr-Tharman-Shanmugaratnam-Deputy-Prime-Minister-and-Minister-for-Finance-for-the-Constitution-of-the-Republic-of-Singapore-(A |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*14 July - The [[Singapore Cable Car|Sentosa Line]], a [[gondola lift]], was opened as a way to get around [[Sentosa]].<ref>{{cite web |title=New cable car service to help visitors get around Sentosa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-cable-car-service-to-help-visitors-get-around-sentosa |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707083028/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-cable-car-service-to-help-visitors-get-around-sentosa |archive-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |date=2015-07-14 }}</ref>\n*24 July - [[2015 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]: The [[List of Singaporean electoral divisions|Electoral Boundaries Review Committee report]] is released. The 13th parliament will consist of 89 members from 29 constituencies (13 Single Member Constituencies and 16 Group Representation Constituencies), up from 87 seats from the current 27 constituencies.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Zakir |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/new-electoral-boundaries-announced-13-smcs-16-grcs-one-in-five-voters-will-see-shift |title=New electoral boundaries announced: 13 SMCs, 16 GRCs, one in five voters will see shift |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=24 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n*9 August - Singapore celebrates its Golden Jubilee at [[Padang, Singapore|Padang]].\n*12 August - The Institute of Southeast Asian Studies (ISEAS) is renamed to [[ISEAS\u2013Yusof Ishak Institute]] to honour [[Yusof Ishak]], Singapore's first [[President of Singapore|President]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Speech by Mr Heng Swee Keat, Minister for Education, at The Ceremony Commemorating The Renaming of The Institute of The Institute of Southeast Asian Studies (ISEAS) as ISEAS - Yusof Ishak Institute, 12 August 2015 |url=https://www.moe.gov.sg/news/speeches/speech-by-mr-heng-swee-keat--minister-for-education--at-the-ceremony-commemorating-the-renaming-of-the-institute-of-the-institute-of-southeast-asian-studies-iseas-as-iseas---yusof-ishak-institute--12-august-2015 |website=MOE |accessdate=18 August 2019 |date=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n*17 August - The [[Organised Crime Act 2015|Organised Crime Act]] is passed to give authorities more power to act against organised crime groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/new-law-giving-authorities-more-powers-against-organised-crime-syndicates |title=New law giving authorities more powers against organised crime syndicates passed |website=The Straits Times |date=17 August 2015 |accessdate=1 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701174905/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/new-law-giving-authorities-more-powers-against-organised-crime-syndicates |archive-date=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n*18 August - The set of six SG50 commemorative notes are unveiled by the [[Monetary Authority of Singapore]] (MAS).<ref>{{cite web |title=Speech by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong at unveiling of SG50 commemorative notes on 18 August 2015 |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-unveiling-sg50-commemorative-notes-18-august-2015 |website=PMO |accessdate=18 August 2019 |date=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n*25 August - \n**The [[Land Transport Authority]] announced that the [[Jurong Region MRT line]] could be extended through [[West Coast, Singapore|West Coast]], terminating at [[Haw Par Villa MRT station]] of the [[Circle MRT line]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Christopher |title=LTA studying possible extension of planned Jurong Region Line to connect to Circle Line |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/lta-studying-possible-extension-of-planned-jurong-region-line-to-connect-to |accessdate=14 July 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=25 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714100239/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/lta-studying-possible-extension-of-planned-jurong-region-line-to-connect-to |archive-date=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n**The [[12th Parliament of Singapore|12th Parliament]] is dissolved.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Min Kok |title=Polling Day on Sept 11, Nomination Day on Sept 1 as general election is called in Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/polling-day-on-sept-11-nomination-day-on-sept-1-as-general-election-is-called-in-singapore |website=The Straits Times |access-date=9 October 2019 |date=25 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n*11 September - [[2015 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]:\n**It was the first general election (post-independence) in which every eligible Singaporean cast their votes as none of the constituencies was returned via [[walkover]], last seen in [[1963 Singaporean general election|1963]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Zakir |title=No walkovers, 2.46m to vote on Sept 11 |publisher=The Straits Times |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/no-walkovers-246m-to-vote-on-sept-11 |accessdate=11 September 2019 |date=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n**The ruling [[People's Action Party]] (PAP), led by [[Lee Hsien Loong]], retains its majority in the elections with 83 out of 89 seats, with an overall vote share of 69.86%.<ref name=GE2015>{{cite web |title=GE2015: Live results |publisher=The Straits Times |url=https://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/singapore-general-election/2015-live-election-results/index.html |accessdate=11 September 2019 |date=11 September 2015}}</ref>\n**Main opposition [[Workers' Party (Singapore)|Workers' Party]] (WP) won the remaining six parliamentary seats from the other two constituencies ([[Aljunied GRC]] and [[Hougang SMC]]). [[Punggol East SMC]] won by the Workers' Party in the [[2013 Punggol East by-election]] was returned to the PAP.<ref name=GE2015 />\n*15 September - \n**The 6th incineration plant will be built in Tuas, to be completed by 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/energy-commodities/hyflux-mitsubishi-heavy-industries-to-build-new-waste-to-energy-plant-in-tuas | title=Hyflux, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries to build new waste-to-energy plant in Tuas | publisher=The Business Times | date=15 September 2015 | accessdate=1 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701174912/https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/energy-commodities/hyflux-mitsubishi-heavy-industries-to-build-new-waste-to-energy-plant-in-tuas | archive-date=1 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> \n**After 8 years in operation, [[DBS Bank]] announced that [[The Islamic Bank of Asia]] will cease operations.<ref>{{cite web |title=DBS to wind down Islamic banking unit |publisher=The Straits Times |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/dbs-to-wind-down-islamic-banking-unit |accessdate=6 August 2019 |date=15 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423074854/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/dbs-to-wind-down-islamic-banking-unit |archive-date=23 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n**The current [[State Courts of Singapore|State Courts Building]] will be retrofitted by 2023 once the State Courts Complex is completed in 2019. The current State Courts Building will eventually house the [[Family Justice Courts of Singapore|Family Justice Courts]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Amir |title=Iconic State Courts building in Havelock Square celebrates 40th anniversary |website=The Straits Times |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/iconic-state-courts-building-in-havelock-square-celebrates-40th-anniversary |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=15 September 2015}}</ref>\n*17 September - [[3688]], a film on [[getai]] is shown in cinemas.\n*24 September - The [[2015 Southeast Asian haze|haze]] in Singapore reached a hazardous range of 313; [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] prompted to close primary and secondary schools on 25 September as a health precaution due to the haze.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Min Kok |last2=Seow |first2=Joanna |last3=Hio |first3=Lester |title=Primary, secondary schools to close on Friday, Sept 25, due to worsening haze |website=The Straits Times |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/environment/primary-secondary-schools-to-close-on-friday-sept-25-due-to-worsening-haze |accessdate=8 September 2019 |date=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== October ===\n*1 October - \n**[[Marrybrown]] opens its first restaurant in iFly Singapore in Sentosa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/lifestyle/food/marrybrown-opens-first-outlet-spore |title=Marrybrown opens outlet in S'pore |website=Todayonline |date=1 October 2015 |accessdate=13 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318200316/http://www.todayonline.com/lifestyle/food/marrybrown-opens-first-outlet-spore |archive-date=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n**The first [[Alstom Metropolis C751C|C751C]] train begins operation on the [[North East MRT line]].\n*6 October - The [[Singapore General Hospital]] reveals a [[Hepatitis C]] outbreak where 22 patients (four deaths inclusive) are infected with the first case detected on 17 April.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Min Kok |title=22 patients in SGH renal ward infected with hepatitis C; 4 patients have died |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/22-patients-in-sgh-renal-ward-infected-with-hepatitis-c-4-patients-have-died |website=The Straits Times |access-date=8 October 2019 |date=6 October 2015}}</ref> As of 8 December, 3 more infections and 4 deaths were disclosed, bringing the total to 25 patients infected (8 deaths inclusive).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khalik |first1=Salma |title=SGH's lapses led to hepatitis C outbreak earlier this year: Independent Review Committee |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/sghs-lapses-led-to-hepatitis-c-outbreak-earlier-this-year-independent-review |website=The Straits Times |access-date=8 October 2019 |date=8 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2015/12/hep-c-outbreak-timeline-of-events/index.html |title=Report on SGH hep C outbreak: How the incident was escalated |website=Straits Times |date=8 December 2015 |accessdate=5 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425034611/https://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2015/12/hep-c-outbreak-timeline-of-events/index.html |archive-date=25 April 2018}}</ref>\n*9 October - A freak lift accident occurs in Jurong, causing an elderly woman's hands to be severed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/womans-hand-severed-after-becoming-stuck-between-hdb-lift-doors |title=Elderly woman's hand severed by lift doors in freak accident |website=Todayonline |date=9 October 2015 |accessdate=8 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708153215/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/womans-hand-severed-after-becoming-stuck-between-hdb-lift-doors |archive-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n*19 October - \n**[[Fusionopolis]] 2 is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-opening-fusionopolis-two |title=Speech by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong at the Opening of Fusionopolis Two |website=PMO |date=19 October 2015 |accessdate=12 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511184714/https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-opening-fusionopolis-two |archive-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n**Due to the [[2015 Southeast Asian haze|haze]], PM2.5 levels reached a record-high of 471 at 11 pm in Western Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=PM2.5 levels hit 471 as haze situation worsens |website=Today |url=https://www.todayonline.com/world/asia/pm25-levels-hit-471-haze-situation-worsens |accessdate=8 September 2019 |date=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n*21 October - [[City Harvest Church Criminal Breach of Trust Case]]: The six [[City Harvest Church]] leaders involved over its largest charity fund misuse (S$50 million) back in 2010 and its arrest on 2012, are all found guilty over breach of trust and Falsification of Accounts.<ref>{{cite web |title=City Harvest trial: All 6 accused, including founder Kong Hee, found guilty of all charges |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/city-harvest-trial-verdict-due-for-six-accused-church-leaders |accessdate=21 October 2015 |website=The Straits Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021204058/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/city-harvest-trial-verdict-due-for-six-accused-church-leaders |archive-date=21 October 2015}}</ref> On 20 November 2015, all six convicted are given jail sentences, with [[Kong Hee]] given the heaviest sentence of 8 years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheong |first1=Danson |last2=Lim |first2=Yi Han |last3=Ng |first3=Huiwen |last4=Lee |first4=Min Kok |title=City Harvest trial: Kong Hee sentenced to 8 years in prison, 5 other church leaders get between 21 months and 6 years |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/city-harvest-trial-kong-hee-sentenced-to-8-years-in-prison-5-other-church |website=The Straits Times |access-date=8 October 2019 |date=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n*29 October - Stage 6 of the [[Circle MRT line]] is announced during a visit to the Tuas Extension, resulting in a full circle. The extension will consist of 3 stations along the future Great Southern Waterfront, stretching a total distance of 4&nbsp;km. The extension will be completed by 2025.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech-by-Acting-Minister-for-Education-Schools-and-Senior-Minister-of-State-for-Transport-Mr-Ng-Chee-Meng-at-the-Announcement-of-Circle-Line-6-Alignment-at-Tuas-Link-Station/ |title=Speech by Acting Minister for Education (Schools) and Senior Minister of State for Transport Mr Ng Chee Meng at the Announcement of Circle Line 6 Alignment at Tuas Link Station |website=MOT |date=29 October 2015 |accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/circle-line-be-full-loop-2025-station-locations-extension-announced |title=Three new stations to close loop on Circle Line |website=Today |date=29 October 2015 |accessdate=23 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612184401/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/circle-line-be-full-loop-2025-station-locations-extension-announced |archive-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> To support these expansions, [[Kim Chuan Depot]] will be expanded to store more trains and includes a bus depot aboveground.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/biggest-underground-train-depot-set-to-become-even-bigger |title=Biggest underground train depot set to become even bigger |website=The Straits Times |date=30 October 2015 |accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== November ===\n[[File:2015 Ma\u2013Xi Meeting 08.jpg|thumb |right |200 px | [[Ma Ying-jeou]] and [[Xi Jinping]] shaking hands at the [[Ma-Xi meeting]] ]]\n* 1 November - [[Healthcare in Singapore#Medishield|MediShield Life]] is launched for all Singaporeans.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khalik |first1=Salma |title=MediShield Life to start on Nov 1 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/medishield-life-to-start-on-nov-1 |accessdate=7 June 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=2 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607142620/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/medishield-life-to-start-on-nov-1 |archive-date=7 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 7 November - The leaders of China and Taiwan [[Ma\u2013Xi meeting|met]] in Singapore, the first such meeting between the leaders of the two sides of the [[Taiwan Strait]] since the end of the [[Chinese Civil War]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Katie|title=Leaders of China and Taiwan set for first talks since 1949 split|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/11/06/asia/china-taiwan-summit/index.html|accessdate=November 7, 2015|agency=CNN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107062519/http://edition.cnn.com/2015/11/06/asia/china-taiwan-summit/index.html|archive-date=November 7, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 21 November - [[Joo Koon Bus Interchange]] officially opened as Singapore's eighth air-conditioned bus interchange.\n* 24 November - \n**The [[National Gallery Singapore]], an [[art museum]], officially opened.\n**[[United Overseas Bank]] (UOB) launches the UOB Mighty app.<ref>{{cite news |title=UOB app enables customers to tap mobile phones for payments |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/uob-app-enables-customers-to-tap-mobile-phones-for-payments |accessdate=9 June 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=24 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609073202/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/uob-app-enables-customers-to-tap-mobile-phones-for-payments |archive-date=9 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== December ===\n*3\u20139 December - [[2015 ASEAN Para Games]] was held in Singapore.\n*4 December -\n**[[The Dream Makers II|The second season]] of the critically acclaimed television drama ''[[The Dream Makers (TV series)|The Dream Makers]]'', which would went on to win a [[The Dream Makers II#Awards and nominations|record-number accolades in Singapore]], premieres on [[Channel 8 (Singapore)|MediaCorp Channel 8]].\n**A mass [[food poisoning]] case occurred where about 150 people were infected with [[Group B streptococcal infection|Group B streptococcal disease]] after consuming freshwater fish prepared raw. The next day, the [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced a ban on using freshwater fish for raw dishes.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-who-fell-ill-eating-raw-fish-out-of-coma | title=Man who fell ill eating raw fish out of coma | publisher=Straits Times | date=4 December 2015 | accessdate=5 April 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212122159/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-who-fell-ill-eating-raw-fish-out-of-coma | archive-date=12 February 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Freshwater fish banned from ready to eat raw fish dishes |url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/freshwater-fish-banned-from-ready-to-eat-raw-fish-dishes |publisher=MOH |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=5 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725175251/https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/freshwater-fish-banned-from-ready-to-eat-raw-fish-dishes |archive-date=25 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*6 December - [[Bulim Bus Depot]] was officially opened during a carnival. This is the first bus depot funded by the [[Land Transport Authority]] after a shift to the bus contracting system.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/bulim-bus-depot/2323524.html | title= Bulim Bus Depot officially opens | publisher= Channel Newsasia | accessdate= 7 December 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151207024317/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/bulim-bus-depot/2323524.html | archive-date= 7 December 2015 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n*7 December - [[Temasek Holdings|Temasek]] will sell [[Neptune Orient Lines]] to [[CMA CGM]]. The transaction was completed in 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.todayonline.com/business/french-shipping-liner-cma-cgm-acquire-nol | title= Temasek to sell entire NOL stake for S$2.3b | publisher= Todayonline | accessdate= 7 December 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151208175254/http://www.todayonline.com/business/french-shipping-liner-cma-cgm-acquire-nol | archive-date= 8 December 2015 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n*8 December - National broadcaster [[Mediacorp]] opens its new campus at Mediapolis@one-north, at the same time unveiling a new logo, starting a move from Caldecott.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/pm-lee-hsien-loong-opening-mediacorps-new-campus-mediapolisone-north-8-december-2015 |title=Opening of Mediacorp Campus at Mediapolis@one-north |website=PMO |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n*15 December - The first phase of the ban on emerging tobacco products like smokeless cigarettes and dissolvable tobacco comes into effect. This is done in a bid to protect the public.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/ban-emerging-tobacco-products-kick-dec | title= Ban on 'emerging' tobacco products to kick off from Dec | publisher= Todayonline | accessdate= 5 July 2019 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190705043658/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/ban-emerging-tobacco-products-kick-dec | archive-date= 5 July 2019 | url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lai |first1=Linette |title=MOH bans new forms of tobacco products from Dec 15, 2015 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/moh-bans-new-forms-of-tobacco-products-from-dec-15-2015 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n*22 December - 2-car trains have started operating on the [[Sengkang LRT line]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Tan |first=Christopher |date=24 December 2015 |title=2-car trains roll out on Sengkang LRT|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/2-car-trains-roll-out-on-sengkang-lrt|work=The Straits Times |access-date=28 October 2017 }}</ref>\n*27 December - The second phase of the [[Downtown MRT Line|Downtown Line]] (which spans from [[Bukit Panjang MRT/LRT station|Bukit Panjang]] to [[Rochor MRT station|Rochor]]) is now open to public.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matthews |first1=Holly |title=More will be done to improve rail reliability: Lui |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/downtown-line-2-opens-dec-27 |publisher=Today |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=6 August 2015}}</ref>\n*28 December - [[Yishun Community Hospital]] opens to the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/new-yishun-community-hospital-opens-to-patients |title=New Yishun Community Hospital opens to patients |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=5 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605184227/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/new-yishun-community-hospital-opens-to-patients |archive-date=5 June 2019 |url-status=live|date=2015-12-28 }}</ref>\n\n== Deaths==\n[[File:Lee Kuan Yew cropped.jpg | thumb |right |120 px | [[Lee Kuan Yew]] ]]\n\n*7 January - [[Subhas Anandan]] - Criminal defence lawyer (b. 1947).<ref>{{cite web |title=Subhas Anandan |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1644_2010-02-17.html |website=NLB |accessdate=7 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701171731/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1644_2010-02-17.html |archive-date=1 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*13 February - [[Koh Lip Lin]] - Ex-PAP MP and Education Pioneer (b. 1936).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Yuen-C |title=Ex-PAP MP Koh Lip Lin dies |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ex-pap-mp-koh-lip-lin-dies |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n*14 March - [[Nurshahrin Shahrudin]] - National silat athlete (b. 1994).<ref>{{cite web |title=Silat: National athlete Nurshahrin Shahrudin, 21, dies in his sleep |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/sport/silat-national-athlete-nurshahrin-shahrudin-21-dies-in-his-sleep |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=18 August 2019 |date=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n*23 March - [[Lee Kuan Yew]] - Former Singapore, and Pioneer Prime Minister (b. 1923).<ref>{{Cite news |title=Singapore's founding father Lee Kuan Yew dies at 91 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-32012346 |work=BBC News |location=London |date=23 March 2015 |access-date=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728211454/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-32012346 |archive-date=28 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*7 August - [[Lee Seng Wee]] - Ex-OCBC Bank chairman and billionaire banker (b. 1930).\n*5 September - [[Goh Eng Wah]] - Founder of [[Eng Wah Global]] (b. 1923).<ref>{{cite web |title=Goh Eng Wah |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_679_2005-01-04.html |website=NLB |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n*14 October - [[Miranda Yap]] - Executive Director of the Bioprocessing Technology Institute at the Agency for Science, Technology and Research of Singapore (A*STAR) (b. 1948)<ref name=stobit>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/leading-scientist-dies-four-years-after-suffering-aneurysm|title=Leading scientist Miranda Yap dies, 4 years after suffering aneurysm|work=Straits Times|author1= Aw Cheng Wei|author2=Chew Hui Min|date=16 October 2015|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n*27 October - [[Tan Keong Choon]] - Rubber tycoon, nephew of [[Tan Kah Kee]] (b. 1918).<ref>{{cite web |title=Tan Keong Choon |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1494_2009-04-09.html |website=NLB |accessdate=7 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716071830/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1494_2009-04-09.html |archive-date=16 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*16 November - [[Kwek Leng Joo]] - Businessman (b. 1953).<ref>{{cite web |title=Kwek Leng Joo |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2018-04-04_095716.html |website=NLB |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n*28 December - [[Tiffany Leong]] - Ex-[[Mediacorp]] actress (b. 1985).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chew |first1=Hui Min |title=Former Mediacorp actress Tiffany Leong dies aged 30 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/former-mediacorp-actress-tiffany-leong-dies-aged-30 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Year in Asia|2015}}\n\n[[Category:2015 in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2015 in Southeast Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2010s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2015 by country|Singapore]]\n", "text_old": "{{Dynamic list}}\n{{Year in Singapore|2015}}\n\nThe following lists events that happened during [[2015]] '''in the [[Singapore|Republic of Singapore]]'''.\n\n==Incumbents==\n*[[President of Singapore|President]]: [[Tony Tan Keng Yam]]\n*[[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]]: [[Lee Hsien Loong]]\n\n==Events==\n===January===\n*1 January - The [[National Youth Council Singapore|National Youth Council]] becomes an autonomous agency since being formed as a [[People's Association]] division in 1989.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/national-youth-council-be-autonomous-agency-under-mccy-jan-1 |title=National Youth Council to be autonomous agency under MCCY from Jan 1 |website=Asiaone |date=29 December 2014 |accessdate=4 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704004416/https://www.asiaone.com/singapore/national-youth-council-be-autonomous-agency-under-mccy-jan-1 |archive-date=4 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n*3 January - The Singaporean car carrier ''[[Hoegh Osaka]]'' runs aground on Bramble Bank of the [[Isle of Wight]], in the entrance to [[Southampton Water]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-hampshire-30670746 | title=Crew rescued from listing Solent car transporter | publisher=BBC News | date=3 January 2015 | accessdate=4 January 2015 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150104030807/http://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-hampshire-30670746 | archive-date=4 January 2015 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n*14 January - [https://web.archive.org/web/20150114110705/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/train-commuters-face/1589068.html First SMRT train service disruption] east-bound train travelling from Joo Koon to Dover.\n*23 January - JTC LaunchPad @ one-north is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |title=Opening of JTC LaunchPad @ one-north |url=https://www.jtc.gov.sg/news-and-publications/speeches/Pages/20150123(SPb).aspx |publisher=JTC Corporation |accessdate=3 August 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151218205004/https://www.jtc.gov.sg/news-and-publications/speeches/Pages/20150123(SPb).aspx |archivedate=18 December 2015 |date=23 January 2015 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*29 January - The [[Liquor Control (Supply and Consumption) Act 2015|Liquor Control (Supply and Consumption) Act]] was passed in Parliament. The law bans drinking in public from 10:30pm to 7am and designated Liquor Control Zones, which took effect on 1 April.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/what-you-can-or-cannot-do-under-the-new-alcohol-law|title=What You Can or Cannot do under the new Alcohol Law|publisher=Straits Times|date=1 April 2015|accessdate=5 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180708221316/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/what-you-can-or-cannot-do-under-the-new-alcohol-law|archive-date=8 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/stricter-alcohol-laws-passed-expected-take-effect-april|title=Stricter alcohol laws passed, expected to take effect in April|publisher=Todayonline|date=29 January 2015|accessdate=6 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190606011118/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/stricter-alcohol-laws-passed-expected-take-effect-april|archive-date=6 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===February===\n*11 February - [[Blk71|BASH]] is launched for [[startups]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Williams |first1=Ann |title=BASH is launched: Biggest facility yet to help grow startups in Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/bash-is-launched-biggest-facility-yet-to-help-grow-startups-in-singapore |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=20 August 2019 |date=11 February 2015}}</ref>\n*16 February - [[JTC Corporation]] and [[Temasek Holdings]] have agreed to merge their subsidiaries to better compete in Asia, first announced on 4 September 2014.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Weizhen |title=Temasek, JTC to merge 4 units into mega-entity |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/temasek-jtc-merge-4-units-mega-entity |website=Today |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=5 September 2014}}</ref> The mergers will involve Ascendas and Singbridge, as well as Surbana and Jurong International Holdings.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/temasek-jtc-give-official-blessing-to-merger-of-subsidiaries |title=Temasek, JTC give official blessing to merger of subsidiaries |website=The Straits Times |date=16 February 2015 |accessdate=1 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701180022/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/companies-markets/temasek-jtc-give-official-blessing-to-merger-of-subsidiaries |archive-date=1 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref> The merger is completed on 10 June, resulting in the formation of [[Ascendas-Singbridge]] (since acquired by [[CapitaLand]]) and [[Surbana Jurong]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Ascendas and Singbridge Complete Merger |url=https://www.ascendas-singbridge.com/-/media/ascendas/files/press-release/press-release-2015/20150610-newsrelease-ascendas-and-singbridge-complete-merger.ashx |website=Ascendas-Singbridge |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=10 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Merger between Surbana International and Jurong International completed |url=https://surbanajurong.com/resources/press-releases/merger-surbana-international-jurong-international-completed/ |website=Surbana Jurong |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=10 June 2015}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n*March - [[Capitol Piazza]] is opened to the public as part of [[Capitol Building, Singapore|Capitol]].\n*10 March - A memorial was launched to commemorate the [[MacDonald House bombing]] that happened 50 years earlier.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lim |first1=Yan Liang |title=Memorial to victims of Konfrontasi unveiled near MacDonald House |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/memorial-to-victims-of-konfrontasi-unveiled-near-macdonald-house |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=23 July 2019 |date=10 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723154859/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/memorial-to-victims-of-konfrontasi-unveiled-near-macdonald-house |archive-date=23 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*11 March - Innosparks (an [[ST Engineering]] subsidiary) launches the AIR+ Smart Mask, which consists of a Smart Mask and the AIR+; a micro ventilator. This will help keep those wearing the mask cool, while giving protection from the haze and pollutants. It is able to fit people of all ages including children and the elderly.<ref>{{cite web |title=ST Engineering's Subsidiary Develops The AIR+ Smart Mask, Brings A New Approach To Protective Mask Technology |url=https://www.stengg.com/en/newsroom/news-releases/st-engineering-subsidiary-develops-the-airplus-smart-mask-brings-a-new-approach-to-protective-mask-technology/ |publisher=ST Engineering |accessdate=20 August 2019 |date=11 March 2015}}</ref>\n*13 March - Laws were passed to clarify that landowners can use up to 30 m underground below the Singapore Height Datum, and allow for acquisition of underground space.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lim |first1=Yvonne |title=Proposed law will allow Govt to acquire specific stratum of underground space |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/proposed-law-will-allow-govt-acquire-specific-stratum-underground-space |accessdate=20 July 2019 |publisher=Todayonline |date=12 February 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720161901/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/proposed-law-will-allow-govt-acquire-specific-stratum-underground-space |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Second Reading Speech by Senior Minister of State for Law, Indranee Rajah SC, on the State Lands (Amendment) Bill 2015 |url=https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/parliamentary-speeches-and-responses/2R-state-lands-amendment-bill-2015.html |publisher=MinLaw |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=13 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720161858/https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/parliamentary-speeches-and-responses/2R-state-lands-amendment-bill-2015.html |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Second Reading Speech by Senior Minister of State for Law, Indranee Rajah SC, on the Land Acquisition (Amendment) Bill 2015 |url=https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/parliamentary-speeches-and-responses/2R-land-acquisition-amendment-bill-2015.html |publisher=MinLaw |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=13 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720161911/https://www.mlaw.gov.sg/content/minlaw/en/news/parliamentary-speeches-and-responses/2R-land-acquisition-amendment-bill-2015.html |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*16 March - [[Eng Wah Global|WE Cinemas]] opens a new multiplex in 321 Clementi, which also opened on the same day. This marked WE Cinemas' re-entry into the cinema business.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lui |first1=John |title=Eng Wah Clementi cineplex opens, marks operator WE Cinemas' return after two years |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/eng-wah-clementi-cineplex-opens-marks-operator-we-cinemas-return-after-two |accessdate=14 August 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=16 March 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190814154122/https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/eng-wah-clementi-cineplex-opens-marks-operator-we-cinemas-return-after-two |archive-date=14 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*23-29 March - [[Death of Lee Kuan Yew]]:\n**23 March -\n***Singapore's first and former [[Prime Minister of Singapore|Prime Minister]] [[Lee Kuan Yew]], notable for his contributions as an \"Architect of Modern Singapore\", passes on at age of 91 at 3:18 am in [[Singapore General Hospital]] due to complications of [[pneumonia]]. \n***Prime Minister [[Lee Hsien Loong]] (who was also the son of the late Lee) declared a seven-day period of national mourning and the funeral will be held on March 29. The state flags on all government buildings would be flown at half-mast for the mourning period, while a majority of television programmings were pre-empted to air a selected series of programs in tribute of Lee.\n**25 March - \n***The funeral procession of Lee from the [[Istana Singapore|Istana]] to [[Parliament House, Singapore|Parliament House]] to lay in state. Later on the same day, the house was opened to Singapore who queued to pay their last respects to Lee.\n**29 March - \n***The funeral procession of Lee from the [[Parliament House, Singapore|Parliament House]] to [[National University of Singapore]] (NUS) University Cultural Centre.\n***Lee's body was cremated and interred at [[Mandai Crematorium and Columbarium]].\n* 29 March - [[Amos Yee]] was arrested for insensitive remarks. He was charged and found guilty, with a jail term imposed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/amos-yee-who-made-insensitive-remarks-on-christianity-in-video-arrested|title=Amos Yee, who made insensitive remarks on Christianity in video, arrested|date=2015-03-30|website=The Straits Times|language=en|access-date=2019-07-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704041430/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/amos-yee-who-made-insensitive-remarks-on-christianity-in-video-arrested|archive-date=2019-07-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n*1 April - \n**[[xinmsn]] ceased operation and its services was transferred to [[MSN]] Singapore and [[Toggle (website)|Toggle]].\n**The [[Cyber Security Agency (Singapore)|Cyber Security Agency]] is formed under the [[Prime Minister's Office (Singapore)|Prime Minister's Office]] to oversee [[cybersecurity]] matters, taking over the Singapore Infocomm Technology Security Authority and the Singapore Computer Emergency Response Team. The agency is first announced on 27 January.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Irene |title=New Cyber Security Agency to be set up in April, Yaacob Ibrahim to be minister in charge of cyber security |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-cyber-security-agency-to-be-set-up-in-april-yaacob-ibrahim-to-be-minister-in-charge-of |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=26 September 2019 |date=27 January 2015}}</ref>\n*8 April - The [[Puss in Boots' Giant Journey]] ride opens in [[Universal Studios Singapore]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee Miller |first1=Shawn |title=New Puss In Boots ride at Universal Studios Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/new-puss-in-boots-ride-at-universal-studios-singapore |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=8 April 2015}}</ref>\n*30 April - Genting Hotel in Jurong was opened, making it the first hotel in west Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Genting Hotel in Jurong to open on Apr 30 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-genting-hotel-in-jurong-to-open-on-apr-30 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707081623/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-genting-hotel-in-jurong-to-open-on-apr-30 |archive-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |date=9 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n===May===\n* 1 May - Fast food chain [[Wendy's]] closes its last outlet in [[National University of Singapore]].\n* 5 May - [[Jurong East]] was chosen as the [[Singapore]] terminus of the [[Kuala Lumpur\u2013Singapore High Speed Rail]], resulting in Jurong Country Club's acquisition on 11 May.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/high-speed-rail-terminus-be-located-jurong-east |title=High Speed Rail terminus to be located in Jurong East |publisher=Todayonline |date=5 May 2015 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804104629/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/high-speed-rail-terminus-be-located-jurong-east |archive-date=4 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/jurong-country-club-make-way-hsr |title=Jurong Country Club to make way for HSR |publisher=Todayonline |date=11 May 2015 |accessdate=4 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190804104631/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/jurong-country-club-make-way-hsr |archive-date=4 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 11 May - New laws to regulate the use of drones are passed.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-new-law-passed-to-regulate-the-use-of-drones | title=Parliament: New law passed to regulate the use of drones | publisher=The Straits Times | date=11 May 2015 | accessdate=1 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701180022/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-new-law-passed-to-regulate-the-use-of-drones | archive-date=1 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> The laws, also known as the Unmanned Aircraft (Public Safety and Security) Act, have come into force on 1 June.\n* 15 May - [[Singapore Botanical Gardens]] gets [[ICOMOS]] nod to be the first [[UNESCO]] [[World Heritage Site]].\n* 19 May - [[Capitol Theatre, Singapore|Capitol Theatre]] was reopened as part of [[Capitol Building, Singapore|Capitol]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/capitol-theatre-to-re-open-10-things-about-the-new-capitol-singapore | title=Capitol Theatre to re-open: 10 things about the new Capitol Singapore | publisher=The Straits Times | date=11 May 2015 | accessdate=11 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190711052007/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/capitol-theatre-to-re-open-10-things-about-the-new-capitol-singapore | archive-date=11 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 21 May - Construction starts on [[Outram Community Hospital]], which will be completed by 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheong |first1=Kash |title=New Outram Community Hospital to ease crunch with additional 550 beds |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/new-outram-community-hospital-to-ease-crunch-with-additional-550-beds |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=8 July 2019 |date=21 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708161114/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/new-outram-community-hospital-to-ease-crunch-with-additional-550-beds |archive-date=8 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 23 May - [[LionsXII]] wins the Malaysian FA Cup for the first time after beating Kelantan, 3-1 in the final at the National Stadium, Bukit Jalil.\n* 27 May - [[Battlestar Galactica (roller coaster)|Battlestar Galactica]] reopens in [[Universal Studios Singapore]] after a two-year closure with new two-seater vehicles.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wee |first1=Cheryl Faith |title=Universal Studios Singapore's main attraction Battlestar Galactica reopens |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/universal-studios-singapores-main-attraction-battlestar-galactica-reopens |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 March 2020 |date=27 May 2015}}</ref>\n* 29 May - The [[National Arts Council, Singapore|National Arts Council]] (NAC) withdraws funding for [[The Art of Charlie Chan Hock Chye]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/national-arts-council-revokes-grant-for-graphic-novel-Sonny-Liew |title=NAC withdraws grant for graphic novel publisher due to \u201csensitive content\u201d |website=Today |date=29 May 2015 |access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref> On 3 June, the NAC added that the book could undermine legitimacy of the [[Singapore government]], thus going against NAC funding rules.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Yong |first1=Charissa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/nac-pulled-grant-from-comic-as-it-potentially-undermines-the-authority-of-the-government |title=NAC pulled grant from comic as it 'potentially undermines the authority of the Government' |website=The Straits Times |date=3 June 2015 |access-date=30 September 2019}}</ref>\n* 31 May - A [[Shooting of Taufik Zahar|police shooting]] took place when a suspect attempted to escape from a police stop, killing one. Two other suspects were arrested and sentenced for drug offences.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/sporean-man-shot-dead-by-police-2-others-detained-in-incident-near-shangri-la | title=S'porean man shot dead by police, 2 others detained in incident near Shangri-La Hotel | publisher=The Straits Times | date=31 May 2015 | accessdate=3 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025140/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/sporean-man-shot-dead-by-police-2-others-detained-in-incident-near-shangri-la | archive-date=3 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/accused-shangri-la-shooting-sentenced | title=Accused in Shangri-La shooting sentenced | publisher=Todayonline | date=21 December 2015 | accessdate=3 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025143/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/accused-shangri-la-shooting-sentenced | archive-date=3 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n===June===\n*5\u201316 June - [[2015 Southeast Asian Games]] was held in Singapore.\n*5 June - [[2015 Sabah earthquake]]: At least nine people, mostly from [[Tanjong Katong Primary School]] (TKPS) were killed when an earthquake measuring 6.0 on Richter scale struck [[Mount Kinabalu]] and [[Ranau]] in the state of [[Sabah]], [[Malaysia]]. A National mourning happened for the victims on 8 June, and [[half-mast]] were flown. As of 10 June, 11 victims were reported after two more were found on Kinabalu.\n*15 June - The [[Infocomm Development Authority]] allows all telcos to shut 2G services from 1 April 2017 to free up capacity for newer 4G services, as well as low subscribership.<ref>{{cite web |title=MNOs to close 2G networks from 1 April 2017 |url=https://www.imda.gov.sg/news-and-events/Media-Room/archived/ida/Media-Releases/2015/mnos-to-close-2g-networks-from-1-april-2017 |website=IDA (now IMDA) |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=15 June 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Irene |title=Singapore pulls plug on 2G mobile networks, to reuse airwaves for newer 4G services |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-pulls-plug-on-2g-mobile-networks-to-reuse-airwaves-for-newer-4g-services |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=17 April 2020 |date=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n*20 June - A police officer was shot by a suspect in [[Khoo Teck Puat Hospital]]. The suspect was sentenced to life with caning in 2018.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/police-officer-shot-duty-khoo-teck-puat-hospital |title=Police officer shot at Khoo Teck Puat Hospital |publisher=Todayonline |date=20 June 2015 |accessdate=3 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025145/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/police-officer-shot-duty-khoo-teck-puat-hospital |archive-date=3 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-shot-police-officer-gets-life-term-in-jail-caning |title=Man who snatched police officer's revolver and fired three shots gets life term in jail, caning |publisher=The Straits Times |date=20 March 2015 |accessdate=3 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190703025407/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/man-who-shot-police-officer-gets-life-term-in-jail-caning |archive-date=3 July 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 22 June - [[Surbana Jurong]] is launched, along with the announcement of several acquisitions to boost its regional standing.<ref>{{cite web |title=Surbana Jurong Private Limited launched, makes two acquisitions in Singapore & China |url=https://surbanajurong.com/resources/press-releases/surbana-jurong-private-limited-launched-makes-two-acquisitions-singapore-china/ |website=Surbana Jurong |accessdate=20 September 2019 |date=22 June 2015}}</ref>\n* 23 June - The third satellite blood collection centre opens in Jurong East.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hsa.gov.sg/content/hsa/en/News_Events/Press_Releases/2015/hsa-opens-third-satellitebloodbankinjurongeast.html|title=HSA Opens Third Satellite Blood Bank in Jurong East|publisher=HSA|date=23 June 2015|accessdate=12 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190712101322/https://www.hsa.gov.sg/content/hsa/en/News_Events/Press_Releases/2015/hsa-opens-third-satellitebloodbankinjurongeast.html|archive-date=12 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mof.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/Speech-by-Mr-Tharman-Shanmugaratnam-Deputy-Prime-Minister-and-Minister-for-Finance-at-the-Opening-of-the-Bloodbank@Westgate-Tower|title=Opening of the Bloodbank@Westgate Tower|publisher=MOF|date=23 June 2015|accessdate=17 August 2019}}</ref>\n* 26 June - The first [[Alstom Metropolis C830C|C830C]] train begins operations on the [[Circle MRT line]].\n* 27 June - [[Kupang LRT station]] is opened for service, along with more trips added, completing the [[Sengkang LRT line]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.sbstransit.com.sg/press/2015-06-15-02.aspx |title=Kupang LRT Station to Open and More than 260 Weekly Trips to be Added to the Sengkang/Punggol LRT |publisher=SBS Transit |access-date=29 August 2019 |date=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n* 30 June - The [[Ng Teng Fong General Hospital]] is opened, along with [[Jurong Community Hospital]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lynette |first1=Tan |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/ng-teng-fong-general-hospital-finally-ready-serve-patients |title=Ng Teng Fong General Hospital finally ready to serve patients |website=Today |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=1 July 2015}}</ref> The hospitals are officially opened on 10 October 2015.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-opening-ng-teng-fong-general-hospital-jurong |title=Opening of Ng Teng Fong General Hospital & Jurong Community Hospital |website=PMO |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=11 October 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/more-hospitals-needed-patient-numbers-due-aging-population-pm-lee |title=As healthcare needs grow, S'pore must continue to get the system right: PM Lee |website=Today |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=10 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n===July===\n*3 July - The first [[Independence-class littoral mission vessel|littoral mission vessel]] (LMV) is launched, going fully operational in 2017. The ships, which were designed and built locally, will have 8 ships when fully commissioned.<ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore launches first of eight new warships that are designed, built locally|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/singapore-launches-first-of-eight-new-warships-that-are-designed-built-locally|publisher=The Straits Times|date=3 July 2015|accessdate=17 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617144412/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/singapore-launches-first-of-eight-new-warships-that-are-designed-built-locally|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Singapore's first Littoral Mission Vessel RSS Independence now fully operational|url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-first-littoral-mission-vessel-rss-independence-now-fully-operational|publisher=The Straits Times|date=5 May 2017|accessdate=17 June 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190617144409/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapores-first-littoral-mission-vessel-rss-independence-now-fully-operational|archive-date=17 June 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> \n*4 July - The 156-year-old [[Singapore Botanic Gardens]] became the first site to receive the status of [[World Heritage Site]] by [[UNESCO]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Zaccheus |first1=Melody |title=Singapore Botanic Gardens clinches prestigious Unesco World Heritage site status |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/singapore-botanic-gardens-clinches-prestigious-unesco-world-heritage-site-status |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=4 July 2015}}</ref>  \n*7 July - The [[North South MRT line|North South]] and [[East West MRT line|East West]] lines are disrupted due to a power fault, making it one of the worst MRT disruptions since 2011.<ref>{{cite web |title=MRT breakdown: North-South, East-West lines down for hours |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/train-services-down-north-south-and-east-west-lines |publisher=Today |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=7 July 2015}}</ref>\n*13 July - \n**[[2015 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]: The [[List of Singaporean electoral divisions|Electoral Boundaries Review Committee]] is announced in [[Parliament of Singapore|Parliament]], having been formed two months ago.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Fang |first1=Joy |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/electoral-boundaries-review-committee-formed-pm |title=Electoral boundaries panel tasked to look into having smaller GRCs |website=Today |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=13 July 2015}}</ref>\n**Amendments to the [[Constitution of Singapore|Constitution]] were passed to include [[Temasek Holdings|Temasek]] into the Net Investment Returns framework from 2016.<ref>{{cite news |last=Tham |first=Yuen-C |title=Parliament: Bill introduced to include more of Temasek's contributions in Govt revenue |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-bill-introduced-to-include-more-of-temaseks-contributions-in-govt-revenue |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=11 May 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720164206/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/parliament-bill-introduced-to-include-more-of-temaseks-contributions-in-govt-revenue |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Second Reading Speech by Mr Tharman Shanmugaratnam, Deputy Prime Minister and Minister for Finance, for the Constitution of the Republic of Singapore (Amendment) Bill 2015 at the Parliament, 13 Jul 2015 |url=https://www.mof.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/Second-Reading-Speech-by-Mr-Tharman-Shanmugaratnam-Deputy-Prime-Minister-and-Minister-for-Finance-for-the-Constitution-of-the-Republic-of-Singapore-(A |publisher=MOF |accessdate=20 July 2019 |date=13 July 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190720164214/https://www.mof.gov.sg/Newsroom/Speeches/Second-Reading-Speech-by-Mr-Tharman-Shanmugaratnam-Deputy-Prime-Minister-and-Minister-for-Finance-for-the-Constitution-of-the-Republic-of-Singapore-(A |archive-date=20 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*14 July - The [[Singapore Cable Car|Sentosa Line]], a [[gondola lift]], was opened as a way to get around [[Sentosa]].<ref>{{cite web |title=New cable car service to help visitors get around Sentosa |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-cable-car-service-to-help-visitors-get-around-sentosa |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=7 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190707083028/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/new-cable-car-service-to-help-visitors-get-around-sentosa |archive-date=7 July 2019 |url-status=live |date=2015-07-14 }}</ref>\n*24 July - [[2015 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]: The [[List of Singaporean electoral divisions|Electoral Boundaries Review Committee report]] is released. The 13th parliament will consist of 89 members from 29 constituencies (13 Single Member Constituencies and 16 Group Representation Constituencies), up from 87 seats from the current 27 constituencies.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Zakir |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/new-electoral-boundaries-announced-13-smcs-16-grcs-one-in-five-voters-will-see-shift |title=New electoral boundaries announced: 13 SMCs, 16 GRCs, one in five voters will see shift |website=The Straits Times |access-date=17 October 2019 |date=24 July 2015}}</ref>\n\n===August===\n*9 August - Singapore celebrates its Golden Jubilee at [[Padang, Singapore|Padang]].\n*12 August - The Institute of Southeast Asian Studies (ISEAS) is renamed to [[ISEAS\u2013Yusof Ishak Institute]] to honour [[Yusof Ishak]], Singapore's first [[President of Singapore|President]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Speech by Mr Heng Swee Keat, Minister for Education, at The Ceremony Commemorating The Renaming of The Institute of The Institute of Southeast Asian Studies (ISEAS) as ISEAS - Yusof Ishak Institute, 12 August 2015 |url=https://www.moe.gov.sg/news/speeches/speech-by-mr-heng-swee-keat--minister-for-education--at-the-ceremony-commemorating-the-renaming-of-the-institute-of-the-institute-of-southeast-asian-studies-iseas-as-iseas---yusof-ishak-institute--12-august-2015 |website=MOE |accessdate=18 August 2019 |date=12 August 2015}}</ref>\n*17 August - The [[Organised Crime Act 2015|Organised Crime Act]] is passed to give authorities more power to act against organised crime groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/new-law-giving-authorities-more-powers-against-organised-crime-syndicates |title=New law giving authorities more powers against organised crime syndicates passed |website=The Straits Times |date=17 August 2015 |accessdate=1 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701174905/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/new-law-giving-authorities-more-powers-against-organised-crime-syndicates |archive-date=1 July 2019}}</ref>\n*18 August - The set of six SG50 commemorative notes are unveiled by the [[Monetary Authority of Singapore]] (MAS).<ref>{{cite web |title=Speech by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong at unveiling of SG50 commemorative notes on 18 August 2015 |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-unveiling-sg50-commemorative-notes-18-august-2015 |website=PMO |accessdate=18 August 2019 |date=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n*25 August - \n**The [[Land Transport Authority]] announced that the [[Jurong Region MRT line]] could be extended through [[West Coast, Singapore|West Coast]], terminating at [[Haw Par Villa MRT station]] of the [[Circle MRT line]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tan |first1=Christopher |title=LTA studying possible extension of planned Jurong Region Line to connect to Circle Line |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/lta-studying-possible-extension-of-planned-jurong-region-line-to-connect-to |accessdate=14 July 2019 |website=The Straits Times |date=25 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190714100239/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/lta-studying-possible-extension-of-planned-jurong-region-line-to-connect-to |archive-date=14 July 2019}}</ref>\n**The [[12th Parliament of Singapore|12th Parliament]] is dissolved.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Min Kok |title=Polling Day on Sept 11, Nomination Day on Sept 1 as general election is called in Singapore |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/polling-day-on-sept-11-nomination-day-on-sept-1-as-general-election-is-called-in-singapore |website=The Straits Times |access-date=9 October 2019 |date=25 August 2015}}</ref>\n\n===September===\n*11 September - [[2015 Singaporean general election|General Elections]]:\n**It was the first general election (post-independence) in which every eligible Singaporean cast their votes as none of the constituencies was returned via [[walkover]], last seen in [[1963 Singaporean general election|1963]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Zakir |title=No walkovers, 2.46m to vote on Sept 11 |publisher=The Straits Times |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/politics/no-walkovers-246m-to-vote-on-sept-11 |accessdate=11 September 2019 |date=2 September 2015}}</ref>\n**The ruling [[People's Action Party]] (PAP), led by [[Lee Hsien Loong]], retains its majority in the elections with 83 out of 89 seats, with an overall vote share of 69.86%.<ref name=GE2015>{{cite web |title=GE2015: Live results |publisher=The Straits Times |url=https://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/singapore-general-election/2015-live-election-results/index.html |accessdate=11 September 2019 |date=11 September 2015}}</ref>\n**Main opposition [[Workers' Party (Singapore)|Workers' Party]] (WP) won the remaining six parliamentary seats from the other two constituencies ([[Aljunied GRC]] and [[Hougang SMC]]). [[Punggol East SMC]] won by the Workers' Party in the [[2013 Punggol East by-election]] was returned to the PAP.<ref name=GE2015 />\n*15 September - \n**The 6th incineration plant will be built in Tuas, to be completed by 2019.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/energy-commodities/hyflux-mitsubishi-heavy-industries-to-build-new-waste-to-energy-plant-in-tuas | title=Hyflux, Mitsubishi Heavy Industries to build new waste-to-energy plant in Tuas | publisher=The Business Times | date=15 September 2015 | accessdate=1 July 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701174912/https://www.businesstimes.com.sg/energy-commodities/hyflux-mitsubishi-heavy-industries-to-build-new-waste-to-energy-plant-in-tuas | archive-date=1 July 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref> \n**After 8 years in operation, [[DBS Bank]] announced that [[The Islamic Bank of Asia]] will cease operations.<ref>{{cite web |title=DBS to wind down Islamic banking unit |publisher=The Straits Times |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/dbs-to-wind-down-islamic-banking-unit |accessdate=6 August 2019 |date=15 September 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190423074854/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/dbs-to-wind-down-islamic-banking-unit |archive-date=23 April 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n**The current [[State Courts of Singapore|State Courts Building]] will be retrofitted by 2023 once the State Courts Complex is completed in 2019. The current State Courts Building will eventually house the [[Family Justice Courts of Singapore|Family Justice Courts]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Hussain |first1=Amir |title=Iconic State Courts building in Havelock Square celebrates 40th anniversary |website=The Straits Times |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/iconic-state-courts-building-in-havelock-square-celebrates-40th-anniversary |accessdate=17 September 2019 |date=15 September 2015}}</ref>\n*17 September - [[3688]], a film on [[getai]] is shown in cinemas.\n*24 September - The [[2015 Southeast Asian haze|haze]] in Singapore reached a hazardous range of 313; [[Ministry of Education (Singapore)|Ministry of Education]] prompted to close primary and secondary schools on 25 September as a health precaution due to the haze.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Min Kok |last2=Seow |first2=Joanna |last3=Hio |first3=Lester |title=Primary, secondary schools to close on Friday, Sept 25, due to worsening haze |website=The Straits Times |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/environment/primary-secondary-schools-to-close-on-friday-sept-25-due-to-worsening-haze |accessdate=8 September 2019 |date=24 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n=== October ===\n*1 October - \n**[[Marrybrown]] opens its first restaurant in iFly Singapore in Sentosa.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/lifestyle/food/marrybrown-opens-first-outlet-spore |title=Marrybrown opens outlet in S'pore |website=Todayonline |date=1 October 2015 |accessdate=13 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180318200316/http://www.todayonline.com/lifestyle/food/marrybrown-opens-first-outlet-spore |archive-date=18 March 2018}}</ref>\n**The first [[Alstom Metropolis C751C|C751C]] train begins operation on the [[North East MRT line]].\n*6 October - The [[Singapore General Hospital]] reveals a [[Hepatitis C]] outbreak where 22 patients (four deaths inclusive) are infected with the first case detected on 17 April.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lee |first1=Min Kok |title=22 patients in SGH renal ward infected with hepatitis C; 4 patients have died |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/22-patients-in-sgh-renal-ward-infected-with-hepatitis-c-4-patients-have-died |website=The Straits Times |access-date=8 October 2019 |date=6 October 2015}}</ref> As of 8 December, 3 more infections and 4 deaths were disclosed, bringing the total to 25 patients infected (8 deaths inclusive).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Khalik |first1=Salma |title=SGH's lapses led to hepatitis C outbreak earlier this year: Independent Review Committee |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/sghs-lapses-led-to-hepatitis-c-outbreak-earlier-this-year-independent-review |website=The Straits Times |access-date=8 October 2019 |date=8 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2015/12/hep-c-outbreak-timeline-of-events/index.html |title=Report on SGH hep C outbreak: How the incident was escalated |website=Straits Times |date=8 December 2015 |accessdate=5 April 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180425034611/https://graphics.straitstimes.com/STI/STIMEDIA/Interactives/2015/12/hep-c-outbreak-timeline-of-events/index.html |archive-date=25 April 2018}}</ref>\n*9 October - A freak lift accident occurs in Jurong, causing an elderly woman's hands to be severed.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/womans-hand-severed-after-becoming-stuck-between-hdb-lift-doors |title=Elderly woman's hand severed by lift doors in freak accident |website=Todayonline |date=9 October 2015 |accessdate=8 July 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190708153215/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/womans-hand-severed-after-becoming-stuck-between-hdb-lift-doors |archive-date=8 July 2019}}</ref>\n*19 October - \n**[[Fusionopolis]] 2 is officially opened.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-opening-fusionopolis-two |title=Speech by Prime Minister Lee Hsien Loong at the Opening of Fusionopolis Two |website=PMO |date=19 October 2015 |accessdate=12 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190511184714/https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/speech-prime-minister-lee-hsien-loong-opening-fusionopolis-two |archive-date=11 May 2019}}</ref>\n**Due to the [[2015 Southeast Asian haze|haze]], PM2.5 levels reached a record-high of 471 at 11 pm in Western Singapore.<ref>{{cite web |title=PM2.5 levels hit 471 as haze situation worsens |website=Today |url=https://www.todayonline.com/world/asia/pm25-levels-hit-471-haze-situation-worsens |accessdate=8 September 2019 |date=20 October 2015}}</ref>\n*21 October - [[City Harvest Church Criminal Breach of Trust Case]]: The six [[City Harvest Church]] leaders involved over its largest charity fund misuse (S$50 million) back in 2010 and its arrest on 2012, are all found guilty over breach of trust and Falsification of Accounts.<ref>{{cite web |title=City Harvest trial: All 6 accused, including founder Kong Hee, found guilty of all charges |url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/city-harvest-trial-verdict-due-for-six-accused-church-leaders |accessdate=21 October 2015 |website=The Straits Times |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151021204058/http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/city-harvest-trial-verdict-due-for-six-accused-church-leaders |archive-date=21 October 2015}}</ref> On 20 November 2015, all six convicted are given jail sentences, with [[Kong Hee]] given the heaviest sentence of 8 years.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Cheong |first1=Danson |last2=Lim |first2=Yi Han |last3=Ng |first3=Huiwen |last4=Lee |first4=Min Kok |title=City Harvest trial: Kong Hee sentenced to 8 years in prison, 5 other church leaders get between 21 months and 6 years |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/courts-crime/city-harvest-trial-kong-hee-sentenced-to-8-years-in-prison-5-other-church |website=The Straits Times |access-date=8 October 2019 |date=20 November 2015}}</ref>\n*29 October - Stage 6 of the [[Circle MRT line]] is announced during a visit to the Tuas Extension, resulting in a full circle. The extension will consist of 3 stations along the future Great Southern Waterfront, stretching a total distance of 4&nbsp;km. The extension will be completed by 2025.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mot.gov.sg/news-centre/news/Detail/Speech-by-Acting-Minister-for-Education-Schools-and-Senior-Minister-of-State-for-Transport-Mr-Ng-Chee-Meng-at-the-Announcement-of-Circle-Line-6-Alignment-at-Tuas-Link-Station/ |title=Speech by Acting Minister for Education (Schools) and Senior Minister of State for Transport Mr Ng Chee Meng at the Announcement of Circle Line 6 Alignment at Tuas Link Station |website=MOT |date=29 October 2015 |accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/circle-line-be-full-loop-2025-station-locations-extension-announced |title=Three new stations to close loop on Circle Line |website=Today |date=29 October 2015 |accessdate=23 May 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612184401/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/circle-line-be-full-loop-2025-station-locations-extension-announced |archive-date=12 June 2018}}</ref> To support these expansions, [[Kim Chuan Depot]] will be expanded to store more trains and includes a bus depot aboveground.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/biggest-underground-train-depot-set-to-become-even-bigger |title=Biggest underground train depot set to become even bigger |website=The Straits Times |date=30 October 2015 |accessdate=18 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== November ===\n[[File:2015 Ma\u2013Xi Meeting 08.jpg|thumb |right |200 px | [[Ma Ying-jeou]] and [[Xi Jinping]] shaking hands at the [[Ma-Xi meeting]] ]]\n* 1 November - [[Healthcare in Singapore#Medishield|MediShield Life]] is launched for all Singaporeans.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Khalik |first1=Salma |title=MediShield Life to start on Nov 1 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/medishield-life-to-start-on-nov-1 |accessdate=7 June 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=2 August 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190607142620/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/medishield-life-to-start-on-nov-1 |archive-date=7 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* 7 November - The leaders of China and Taiwan [[Ma\u2013Xi meeting|met]] in Singapore, the first such meeting between the leaders of the two sides of the [[Taiwan Strait]] since the end of the [[Chinese Civil War]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Hunt|first1=Katie|title=Leaders of China and Taiwan set for first talks since 1949 split|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2015/11/06/asia/china-taiwan-summit/index.html|accessdate=November 7, 2015|agency=CNN|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151107062519/http://edition.cnn.com/2015/11/06/asia/china-taiwan-summit/index.html|archive-date=November 7, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* 21 November - [[Joo Koon Bus Interchange]] officially opened as Singapore's eighth air-conditioned bus interchange.\n* 24 November - \n**The [[National Gallery Singapore]], an [[art museum]], officially opened.\n**[[United Overseas Bank]] (UOB) launches the UOB Mighty app.<ref>{{cite news |title=UOB app enables customers to tap mobile phones for payments |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/uob-app-enables-customers-to-tap-mobile-phones-for-payments |accessdate=9 June 2019 |publisher=The Straits Times |date=24 November 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609073202/https://www.straitstimes.com/business/banking/uob-app-enables-customers-to-tap-mobile-phones-for-payments |archive-date=9 June 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n=== December ===\n*3\u20139 December - [[2015 ASEAN Para Games]] was held in Singapore.\n*4 December -\n**[[The Dream Makers II|The second season]] of the critically acclaimed television drama ''[[The Dream Makers (TV series)|The Dream Makers]]'', which would went on to win a [[The Dream Makers II#Awards and nominations|record-number accolades in Singapore]], premieres on [[Channel 8 (Singapore)|MediaCorp Channel 8]].\n**A mass [[food poisoning]] case occurred where about 150 people were infected with [[Group B streptococcal infection|Group B streptococcal disease]] after consuming freshwater fish prepared raw. The next day, the [[Ministry of Health (Singapore)|Ministry of Health]] announced a ban on using freshwater fish for raw dishes.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-who-fell-ill-eating-raw-fish-out-of-coma | title=Man who fell ill eating raw fish out of coma | publisher=Straits Times | date=4 December 2015 | accessdate=5 April 2019 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190212122159/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/man-who-fell-ill-eating-raw-fish-out-of-coma | archive-date=12 February 2019 | url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Freshwater fish banned from ready to eat raw fish dishes |url=https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/freshwater-fish-banned-from-ready-to-eat-raw-fish-dishes |publisher=MOH |accessdate=25 July 2019 |date=5 December 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190725175251/https://www.moh.gov.sg/news-highlights/details/freshwater-fish-banned-from-ready-to-eat-raw-fish-dishes |archive-date=25 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*6 December - [[Bulim Bus Depot]] was officially opened during a carnival. This is the first bus depot funded by the [[Land Transport Authority]] after a shift to the bus contracting system.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/bulim-bus-depot/2323524.html | title= Bulim Bus Depot officially opens | publisher= Channel Newsasia | accessdate= 7 December 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151207024317/http://www.channelnewsasia.com/news/singapore/bulim-bus-depot/2323524.html | archive-date= 7 December 2015 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n*7 December - [[Temasek Holdings|Temasek]] will sell [[Neptune Orient Lines]] to [[CMA CGM]]. The transaction was completed in 2016.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.todayonline.com/business/french-shipping-liner-cma-cgm-acquire-nol | title= Temasek to sell entire NOL stake for S$2.3b | publisher= Todayonline | accessdate= 7 December 2015 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20151208175254/http://www.todayonline.com/business/french-shipping-liner-cma-cgm-acquire-nol | archive-date= 8 December 2015 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n*8 December - National broadcaster [[Mediacorp]] opens its new campus at Mediapolis@one-north, at the same time unveiling a new logo, starting a move from Caldecott.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.pmo.gov.sg/Newsroom/pm-lee-hsien-loong-opening-mediacorps-new-campus-mediapolisone-north-8-december-2015 |title=Opening of Mediacorp Campus at Mediapolis@one-north |website=PMO |access-date=6 September 2019 |date=8 December 2015}}</ref>\n*15 December - The first phase of the ban on emerging tobacco products like smokeless cigarettes and dissolvable tobacco comes into effect. This is done in a bid to protect the public.<ref>{{cite web | url= https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/ban-emerging-tobacco-products-kick-dec | title= Ban on 'emerging' tobacco products to kick off from Dec | publisher= Todayonline | accessdate= 5 July 2019 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20190705043658/https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/ban-emerging-tobacco-products-kick-dec | archive-date= 5 July 2019 | url-status= live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Lai |first1=Linette |title=MOH bans new forms of tobacco products from Dec 15, 2015 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/moh-bans-new-forms-of-tobacco-products-from-dec-15-2015 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=30 March 2020 |date=15 June 2015}}</ref>\n*22 December - 2-car trains have started operating on the [[Sengkang LRT line]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Tan |first=Christopher |date=24 December 2015 |title=2-car trains roll out on Sengkang LRT|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/transport/2-car-trains-roll-out-on-sengkang-lrt|work=The Straits Times |access-date=28 October 2017 }}</ref>\n*27 December - The second phase of the [[Downtown MRT Line|Downtown Line]] (which spans from [[Bukit Panjang MRT/LRT station|Bukit Panjang]] to [[Rochor MRT station|Rochor]]) is now open to public.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Matthews |first1=Holly |title=More will be done to improve rail reliability: Lui |url=https://www.todayonline.com/singapore/downtown-line-2-opens-dec-27 |publisher=Today |accessdate=6 September 2019 |date=6 August 2015}}</ref>\n*28 December - [[Yishun Community Hospital]] opens to the public.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/new-yishun-community-hospital-opens-to-patients |title=New Yishun Community Hospital opens to patients |publisher=The Straits Times |accessdate=5 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190605184227/https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/new-yishun-community-hospital-opens-to-patients |archive-date=5 June 2019 |url-status=live|date=2015-12-28 }}</ref>\n\n== Deaths==\n[[File:Lee Kuan Yew cropped.jpg | thumb |right |120 px | [[Lee Kuan Yew]] ]]\n\n*7 January - [[Subhas Anandan]] - Criminal defence lawyer (b. 1947).<ref>{{cite web |title=Subhas Anandan |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1644_2010-02-17.html |website=NLB |accessdate=7 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190701171731/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1644_2010-02-17.html |archive-date=1 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*13 February - [[Koh Lip Lin]] - Ex-PAP MP and Education Pioneer (b. 1936).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tham |first1=Yuen-C |title=Ex-PAP MP Koh Lip Lin dies |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/ex-pap-mp-koh-lip-lin-dies |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=14 February 2015}}</ref>\n*14 March - [[Nurshahrin Shahrudin]] - National silat athlete (b. 1994).<ref>{{cite web |title=Silat: National athlete Nurshahrin Shahrudin, 21, dies in his sleep |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/sport/silat-national-athlete-nurshahrin-shahrudin-21-dies-in-his-sleep |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=18 August 2019 |date=14 March 2015}}</ref>\n*23 March - [[Lee Kuan Yew]] - Former Singapore, and Pioneer Prime Minister (b. 1923).<ref>{{Cite news |title=Singapore's founding father Lee Kuan Yew dies at 91 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-32012346 |work=BBC News |location=London |date=23 March 2015 |access-date=25 June 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180728211454/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-asia-32012346 |archive-date=28 July 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*7 August - [[Lee Seng Wee]] - Ex-OCBC Bank chairman and billionaire banker (b. 1930).\n*5 September - [[Goh Eng Wah]] - Founder of [[Eng Wah Global]] (b. 1923).<ref>{{cite web |title=Goh Eng Wah |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_679_2005-01-04.html |website=NLB |accessdate=12 November 2019}}</ref>\n*14 October - [[Miranda Yap]] - Executive Director of the Bioprocessing Technology Institute at the Agency for Science, Technology and Research of Singapore (A*STAR) (b. 1948)<ref name=stobit>{{cite news|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/singapore/health/leading-scientist-dies-four-years-after-suffering-aneurysm|title=Leading scientist Miranda Yap dies, 4 years after suffering aneurysm|work=Straits Times|author1= Aw Cheng Wei|author2=Chew Hui Min|date=16 October 2015|accessdate=18 October 2015}}</ref>\n*27 October - [[Tan Keong Choon]] - Rubber tycoon, nephew of [[Tan Kah Kee]] (b. 1918).<ref>{{cite web |title=Tan Keong Choon |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1494_2009-04-09.html |website=NLB |accessdate=7 August 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716071830/http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_1494_2009-04-09.html |archive-date=16 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*16 November - [[Kwek Leng Joo]] - Businessman (b. 1953).<ref>{{cite web |title=Kwek Leng Joo |url=http://eresources.nlb.gov.sg/infopedia/articles/SIP_2018-04-04_095716.html |website=NLB |accessdate=21 August 2019}}</ref>\n*28 December - [[Tiffany Leong]] - Ex-[[Mediacorp]] actress (b. 1985).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Chew |first1=Hui Min |title=Former Mediacorp actress Tiffany Leong dies aged 30 |url=https://www.straitstimes.com/lifestyle/entertainment/former-mediacorp-actress-tiffany-leong-dies-aged-30 |website=The Straits Times |accessdate=29 October 2019 |date=28 December 2015}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Years in Singapore}}\n{{Year in Asia|2015}}\n\n[[Category:2015 in Singapore| ]]\n[[Category:Years of the 21st century in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2015 in Southeast Asia|Singapore]]\n[[Category:2010s in Singapore]]\n[[Category:2015 by country|Singapore]]\n", "name_user": "TheGreatSG'rean", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eJune", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2015_in_Singapore"}
{"title_page": "Guernica (Picasso)", "text_new": "{{Infobox Painting\n| image_file=PicassoGuernica.jpg\n| image_size=350px\n| title=Guernica\n| artist=[[Pablo Picasso]]\n| year = 1937\n| medium=[[Oil painting|Oil on canvas]]\n| width_metric=776.6\n| height_metric=349.3\n| width_imperial =305.5\n| height_imperial=137.4\n| city=[[Madrid]], [[Spain]]\n| museum=[[Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda|Museo Reina Sof\u00eda]]\n}}\n\n'''''Guernica''''' ({{IPA-es|\u0261e\u027e\u02c8nika|lang}}, {{IPA-eu|\u0261ernika|lang}}) is a large 1937 oil painting on canvas by [[Spain|Spanish]] artist [[Pablo Picasso]].<ref name=\"Richardson_2016\">Richardson (2016)</ref><ref name=\"measures\">Picasso, Pablo. ''[http://www.museoreinasofia.es/coleccion/obra/guernica Guernica.]'' [[Museo Reina Sof\u00eda]]. ''(Retrieved 2017-09-07.)''</ref>  One of Picasso's best known works, ''Guernica'' is regarded by many art critics as one of the most moving and powerful [[anti-war]] paintings in history,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.biography.com/people/pablo-picasso-9440021#surrealism |title=Pablo Picasso |website=Biography.com}}</ref> It is exhibited in the [[Museo Reina Sof\u00eda]] in Madrid.\n\nThe gray, black, and white painting, which is {{convert|3.49|m|ftin|sp=us}} tall and {{convert|7.76|m|ftin|sp=us}} across, portrays the suffering of people and animals wrenched by violence and chaos. Prominent in the composition are a gored horse, a bull, screaming women, dismemberment, and flames.\n\nPicasso painted ''Guernica'' at his home in Paris in response to the [[bombing of Guernica]], a [[Basque Country (greater region)|Basque Country]] [[Guernica (town)|town]] in northern [[Spain]], by [[Nazi Germany]] and [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Fascist Italy]] at the request of the Spanish [[Spain under Franco|Nationalists]]. Upon completion, ''Guernica'' was exhibited at the Spanish display at the [[Exposition Internationale des Arts et Techniques dans la Vie Moderne|1937 Paris International Exposition]], and then at other venues around the world. The touring exhibition was used to raise funds for Spanish war relief.<ref name=\"Cohen_2003\"/> The painting soon became famous and widely acclaimed, and it helped bring worldwide attention to the [[Spanish Civil War]].\n\n==Commission==\nIn January 1937, while Pablo Picasso was living in Paris on Rue des Grands Augustins, he was commissioned by the [[Second Spanish Republic|Spanish Republican]] government to create a large [[mural]] for the Spanish pavilion at the [[1937 Paris World's Fair]]. Picasso, who had last visited Spain in 1934 and would never return, was the Honorary Director-in-Exile of the [[Prado Museum]].<ref name=\"timeline\" />\n\nPicasso worked somewhat dispassionately from January until late April on the project's initial sketches, which depicted his perennial theme of an artist's studio.<ref name=\"Richardson_2016\"/> Then, immediately upon hearing reports of the 26 April bombing of Guernica, poet [[Juan Larrea (poet)|Juan Larrea]] visited Picasso's home to urge him to make the bombing his subject.<ref name=\"Richardson_2016\"/> Days later, on 1 May, Picasso read [[George Steer]]'s eyewitness account of the attack, which originally had been published in both ''[[The Times]]'' and ''[[The New York Times]]'' on 28 April, and abandoned his initial idea. Acting on Larrea's suggestion, Picasso began sketching a series of preliminary drawings for ''Guernica''.<ref>[[Preston, Paul]] (2012) [https://books.google.com/books?id=LOpqVkAyFkAC&printsec=frontcover&dq=Steer%27s+report+preston ''The Destruction of Guernica''. HarperCollins] At Google Books. Retrieved 18 July 2013.</ref>\n\n==Historical context==\n{{See also|Bombing of Guernica|Spanish Civil War|Spanish Civil War, 1937}}\n\n===Bombing of 26 April 1937===\nDuring the Spanish Civil War, the Republican forces were made up of assorted factions such as communists, socialists, anarchists, and others with differing goals. Yet they were united in their opposition to the Nationalists, led by General [[Francisco Franco]], who sought a return to pre-Republican Spain based on law, order, and traditional Catholic values.<ref>Barton (2004).</ref>\n\n[[Guernica (town)|Guernica]], a town in the province of [[Biscay]] in Basque Country, was seen as the northern bastion of the Republican resistance movement and the center of Basque culture. This added to its significance as a target.<ref name = Arhheim1973>Arhheim, (1973) p. ???</ref> Around 4:30 p.m. on Monday, 26 April 1937, warplanes of the [[Nazi Germany]] [[Condor Legion]], commanded by Colonel [[Wolfram von Richthofen]], bombed Guernica for about two hours.<ref name=Ray2006>Ray (2006), 168\u2013171.</ref><ref name=Arhheim1973/> In his journal for 30 April 1937, von Richthofen wrote:\n{{quote|When the first Junkers squadron arrived, there was smoke already everywhere (from the VB [VB/88] which had attacked with 3 aircraft); nobody would identify the targets of roads, bridge, and suburb, and so they just dropped everything right into the center. The 250s toppled a number of houses and destroyed the water mains. The incendiaries now could spread and become effective. The materials of the houses: tile roofs, wooden porches, and half-timbering resulted in complete annihilation. Most inhabitants were away because of a holiday; a majority of the rest left town immediately at the beginning [of the bombardment]. A small number perished in shelters that were hit.\"<ref> Quoted in Oppler (1988), p. 166.</ref>}}\n\nOther accounts state that since it was Guernica's market day, its inhabitants were congregated in the center of town. When the bombardment began they were unable to escape because the roads were full of debris and the bridges leading out of town had been destroyed.\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 183-H25224, Guernica, Ruinen.jpg|right|thumb|Guernica in ruins, 1937]]\nGuernica was a quiet village 10 kilometers from the front lines, and in-between the front lines and Bilbao, the capital of Bizkaia ([[Biscay]]). But any Republican retreat towards Bilbao, or any Nationalist advance towards Bilbao, had to pass through Guernica.<ref>Beevor (2006), 231</ref> Wolfram von Richthofen's war diary entry for 26 April 1937 states, \"K/88 [the Condor Legion bomber force] was targeted at Guernica in order to halt and disrupt the Red withdrawal which has to pass through here.\" Under the German concept of tactical bombing, areas that were routes of transportation and troop movement were considered legitimate military targets. The following day, Richthofen wrote in his war diary, \"Guernica burning.\"<ref name=\"beevor233\">Beevor (2006), 233.</ref>  \n\nThe nearest military target of any consequence was a war product factory on Guernica's outskirts, but it went through the attack unscathed. Thus, the attack was widely condemned as a terror bombing.<ref>Saul, Toby (8 May 2018). [https://www.nationalgeographic.com/archaeology-and-history/magazine/2018/05-06/pablo-picasso-guernica-painting-history/ \"The horrible inspiration behind one of Picasso's great works\"]. nationalgeographic.com. Retrieved 21 May 2019. </ref><ref>Overy, Richard (2013). ''[https://books.google.com/books?id=eEcXfXoSdgwC&printsec=frontcover&dq= The Bombing War: Europe, 1939-1945]''. Penguin UK. p. ix. {{ISBN|0141927828}}.</ref>\n\n===Guernica's aftermath===\nBecause a majority of Guernica's men were away, fighting on behalf of the Republicans, at the time of the bombing the town was populated mostly by women and children.<ref name=Preston2007>Preston (2007). 12\u201319.</ref> These demographics are reflected in ''Guernica''. As [[Rudolf Arnheim]] writes, for Picasso: \"The women and children make ''Guernica'' the image of innocent, defenseless humanity victimized. Also, women and children have often been presented by Picasso as the very perfection of mankind. An assault on women and children is, in Picasso's view, directed at the core of mankind.\"<ref name=Arhheim1973/>\n\n''The Times'' journalist [[George Steer]], a Basque and Republican sympathizer, propelled this event onto the international scene and brought it to Pablo Picasso's attention. Steer's eyewitness account was published on 28 April in both ''The Times'' and ''The New York Times'', and on the 29th it appeared in ''[[L'Humanit\u00e9]]'', a French Communist daily. Steer wrote:\n\n{{quote|Guernica, the most ancient town of the Basques and the centre of their cultural tradition, was completely destroyed yesterday afternoon by insurgent air raiders. The bombardment of this open town far behind the lines occupied precisely three hours and a quarter, during which a powerful fleet of aeroplanes consisting of three types of German types, Junkers and Heinkel bombers, did not cease unloading on the town bombs weighing from 1,000 lbs. downwards and, it is calculated, more than 3,000 two-pounder aluminium incendiary projectiles. The fighters, meanwhile, plunged low from above the centre of the town to machinegun those of the civilian population who had taken refuge in the fields.\"<ref name=Preston2007/>}}\n\nPicasso lived in Paris during the [[German military administration in occupied France during World War II|German occupation]] during World War II. A German officer allegedly asked him, upon seeing a photo of ''Guernica'' in Picasso's apartment, \"Did you do that?\" Picasso responded, \"No, you did.\"<ref>{{cite web|author=Tom Lubbock |url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2005/jan/08/highereducation.news |title=Review: Guernica by Gijs van Hensbergen &#124; Books |publisher=The Guardian |date=27 March 2013 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Creation==\n''Guernica'' was painted using a matte house paint specially formulated at Picasso's request to have the least possible gloss.<ref name=\"Richardson_2016\"/> American artist [[John Ferren]] assisted him in stretching the monumental canvas,<ref>[https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/john-ferren]</ref> and photographer [[Dora Maar]], who had been working with Picasso since mid-1936 photographing his studio and teaching him the technique of [[photogram|cameraless photography]],<ref>Fluegel (1980), p. 308.</ref> documented its creation. Apart from their documentary and publicity value, Maar's photographs \"helped Picasso to eschew color and give the work the black-and-white immediacy of a photograph\", according to art historian [[John Richardson (art historian)|John Richardson]].<ref name=\"Richardson_2016\"/><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/john-ferren |title=Archived copy |access-date=29 July 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170729100546/https://www.guggenheim.org/artwork/artist/john-ferren |archive-date=29 July 2017 |url-status=bot: unknown }}</ref>\n\nPicasso, who rarely allowed strangers into his studio to watch him work, admitted influential visitors to observe his progress on ''Guernica'', believing that the publicity would help the antifascist cause.<ref name=\"Richardson_2016\"/> As his work on the mural progressed, Picasso explained: \"The Spanish struggle is the fight of reaction against the people, against freedom. My whole life as an artist has been nothing more than a continuous struggle against reaction and the death of art. How could anybody think for a moment that I could be in agreement with reaction and death? ... In the panel on which I am working, which I shall call ''Guernica'', and in all my recent works of art, I clearly express my abhorrence of the military caste which has sunk Spain in an ocean of pain and death.\"<ref>T\u00f3ib\u00edn (2006).</ref>\n\nPicasso worked on the painting for 35 days, and finished it on 4 June 1937.<ref name=\"Richardson_2016\"/> picasso had really cool and amazing creations. Art was part of him\n\n==Composition==\n{{refimprove section|date=April 2017}}\n[[File:PicassoGuernica.jpg|thumb|470px|center]]\nThe scene occurs within a room where, on the left, a wide-eyed bull stands over a grieving woman holding a dead child in her arms. In the center of the room a horse falls in agony with a large gaping hole in its side, as if it had just been run through by a spear or javelin. The horse appears to be wearing chain mail armor, decorated with vertical tally marks arranged in rows.\n\nA dead and dismembered soldier lies under the horse. The hand of his severed right arm grasps a shattered sword, from which a flower grows. The open palm of the soldier's left hand contains a stigma, a symbol of martyrdom derived from the [[stigmata]] of Christ. A bare light bulb in the shape of an eye blazes over the suffering horse's head.\n\nTo the horse's upper right a frightened female figure appears to have floated into the room through a window, and witnesses the scene. She carries a flame-lit lamp, and holds it near the bare bulb. From the right, below the floating figure, an awe-struck woman staggers towards the center, looking into the blazing light bulb with a blank stare.\n\nDaggers that suggest screaming have replaced the tongues of the horse, the bull, and the grieving woman. A dove is scribed on the wall behind the bull, part of its body comprising a crack in the wall through which bright light from the outside shines.\n\nOn the far right another woman, her arms raised in terror, is entrapped by fire from above and below. Her right hand suggests the shape of an airplane. A dark wall with an open door defines the right side of the room.\n\nTwo \"hidden\" images formed by the horse appear in ''Guernica'':\n* A human skull overlays the horse's body.\n* A bull appears to gore the horse from underneath. The bull's head is formed mainly by the horse's entire front leg which has the knee on the ground. The leg's knee cap forms the head's nose. A horn appears within the horse's breast. The bull's tail forms the image of a flame with smoke rising from it, seemingly appearing in a window created by the lighter shade of gray surrounding it.\n\n==Symbolism and interpretations==\nInterpretations of ''Guernica'' vary widely and contradict one another. This extends, for example, to the mural's two dominant elements: the bull and the horse. Art historian Patricia Failing said, \"The bull and the horse are important characters in Spanish culture. Picasso himself certainly used these characters to play many different roles over time. This has made the task of interpreting the specific meaning of the bull and the horse very tough. Their relationship is a kind of ballet that was conceived in a variety of ways throughout Picasso's career.\"\n\nWhen pressed to explain the elements in ''Guernica'', Picasso said,\n\n{{quote|...this bull is a bull and this horse is a horse... If you give a meaning to certain things in my paintings it may be very true, but it is not my idea to give this meaning. What ideas and conclusions you have got I obtained too, but instinctively, unconsciously. I make the painting for the painting. I paint the objects for what they are.<ref>[https://www.pbs.org/treasuresoftheworld/a_nav/guernica_nav/gnav_level_1/5meaning_guerfrm.html ...questions of meaning], part of a series of web pages on ''Guernica'' in [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS's]] ''Treasures of the World'' series. Accessed 16 July 2006.</ref>}}\n\nIn ''[[The Dream and Lie of Franco]]'', a series of narrative sketches Picasso also created for the World's Fair, [[Francisco Franco|Franco]] is depicted as a monster that first devours his own horse and later does battle with an angry bull. Work on these illustrations began before the bombing of Guernica, and four additional panels were added, three of which relate directly to the Guernica mural.\n\nAccording to scholar Beverly Ray, the following list of interpretations reflects the general consensus of historians: \"The shape and posture of the bodies express protest\"; \"Picasso uses black, white, and grey paint to set a somber mood and express pain and chaos\"; \"flaming buildings and crumbling walls not only express the destruction of Guernica, but reflect the destructive power of civil war\"; \"the newspaper print used in the painting reflects how Picasso learned of the massacre\"; \"The light bulb in the painting represents the sun\"; and \"The broken sword near the bottom of the painting symbolizes the defeat of the people at the hand of their tormentors\".<ref name=Ray2006/>\n\nAlejandro Escalona said, \"The chaos unfolding seems to happen in closed quarters provoking an intense feeling of oppression. There is no way out of the nightmarish cityscape. The absence of color makes the violent scene developing right before your eyes even more horrifying. The blacks, whites, and grays startle you\u2014especially because you are used to see war images broadcast live and in high-definition right to your living room.\"<ref name = \"75years\" />\n\nIn drawing attention to a number of preliminary studies, the so-called primary project,<ref>[[Werner Spies]]: Guernica und die Weltausstellung von 1937. In: Id.: Kontinent Picasso. Ausgew\u00e4hlte Aufs\u00e4tze, Munich 1988, S. 63\u201399.</ref> that show an atelier installation incorporating the central triangular shape which reappears in the final version of ''Guernica'', Becht-J\u00f6rdens and Wehmeier interpret the painting as a self-referential composition in the tradition of atelier paintings such as ''[[Las Meninas]]'' by [[Diego Vel\u00e1zquez]]. In his ''chef d'oeuvre'', Picasso seems to be trying to define his role and his power as an artist in the face of political power and violence. But far from being a mere political painting, ''Guernica'' should be seen as Picasso's comment on what art can actually contribute towards the self-assertion that liberates every human being and protects the individual against overwhelming forces such as political crime, war, and death.<ref>See Becht-J\u00f6rdens (2003)</ref>\n\n==Exhibition==\n===1937 Paris International Exhibition===\n''Guernica'' was unveiled and initially exhibited in July 1937 at the Spanish Pavilion at the [[Exposition Internationale des Arts et Techniques dans la Vie Moderne|Paris International Exposition]].<ref>Martin (2002)</ref>, where Nazi Germany and Stalinist Russia had huge pavilions. The Pavilion, which was financed by the Spanish Republican government at the time of civil war, was built to exhibit the Spanish government's struggle for existence contrary to the Exposition's technology theme. The Pavilion's entrance presented an enormous photographic mural of Republican soldiers accompanied by the slogan:\n\n:We are fighting for the essential unity of Spain.\n:We are fighting for the integrity of Spanish soil.\n:We are fighting for the independence of our country and for\n:the right of the Spanish people to determine their own destiny.\n\nThe display of ''Guernica'' was accompanied by a poem by [[Paul \u00c9luard]], and the pavilion displayed ''[[The Reaper (Mir\u00f3 painting)|The Reaper]]'' by [[Joan Mir\u00f3]] and ''[[Mercury fountain|Mercury Fountain]]'' by [[Alexander Calder]], both of whom were sympathetic to the Republican cause.\n\nAt ''Guernica''{{'}}s Paris Exhibition unveiling it garnered little attention. The public's reaction to the painting was mixed.<ref>Witham (2013), p. 175.</ref> [[Max Aub]], one of the officials in charge of the Spanish pavilion, was compelled to defend the work against a group of Spanish officials who objected to the mural's modernist style and sought to replace it with a more traditional painting that was also commissioned for the exhibition, ''Madrid 1937 (Black Aeroplanes)'' by Horacio Ferrer de Morgado.<ref name=\"Richardson_2016\"/> Some Marxist groups criticized Picasso's painting as lacking in political commitment, and faulted it for not offering a vision of a better future.<ref>Greeley, Robin A. (2006). ''Surrealism and the Spanish Civil War''. New Haven: Yale University Press. p. 241. {{ISBN|0300112955}}</ref> In contrast, Morgado's painting was a great success with Spanish Communists and with the public.<ref name=\"Richardson_2016\"/> The art critic [[Clement Greenberg]] was also critical of ''Guernica'',<ref>Witham (2013), p. 176</ref> and in a later essay he termed the painting \"jerky\" and \"too compressed for its size\", and compared it unfavorably to the \"magnificently lyrical\" ''[[The Charnel House]]'' (1944\u20131948), a later antiwar painting by Picasso.<ref>Greenberg (1993), p. 236.</ref>\n\nAmong the painting's admirers were art critic [[Jean Cassou]] and poet [[Jos\u00e9 Bergam\u00edn]], both of whom praised the painting as quintessentially Spanish.<ref>Martin (2003), p. 128.</ref> [[Michel Leiris]] perceived in ''Guernica'' a foreshadowing: \"On a black and white canvas that depicts ancient tragedy ... Picasso also writes our letter of doom: all that we love is going to be lost...\"<ref>Martin (2003), p. 129.</ref>\n\n===European tour===\n''Guernica'', for which Picasso was paid 200,000 francs for his costs by the Spanish Republican government, was one of the few major paintings that Picasso did not sell directly to his exclusive contracted [[art dealer]] and friend, [[Paul Rosenberg (art dealer)|Paul Rosenberg]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=7MbJ7bzsbo8C&pg=PA83&lpg=PA83 Van Hensbergen, Gijs (2005) ''Guernica'' p. 83 Bloomsbury Publishing] At Google Books. Retrieved 4 November 2013</ref> However, after its exhibition Rosenberg organised a four-man extravaganza [[Scandinavia]]n tour of 118 works by Picasso, [[Matisse]], [[Braque]], and [[Henri Laurens]]. The tour's main attraction was ''Guernica''.\n\nFrom January to April 1938 the tour visited [[Oslo]], [[Copenhagen]], [[Stockholm]], and [[Gothenburg|G\u00f6teborg]]. Starting in late September ''Guernica'' was exhibited in [[London]]'s [[Whitechapel Art Gallery]]. This stop was organized by [[Roland Penrose|Sir Roland Penrose]] with Labour Party leader [[Clement Attlee]], and the painting arrived in London on 30 September, the same day the [[Munich Agreement]] was signed by the leaders of the United Kingdom, France, Italy, and Germany. It then travelled to [[Leeds]], [[Liverpool]], and, in early 1939, [[Manchester]]. There, Manchester Foodship For Spain, a group of artists and activists engaged in sending aid to the people of Spain, exhibited the painting in the HE Nunn & Co Ford automobile showroom for two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Youngs |first=Ian |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-16927120 |title=BBC News \u2013 Picasso's Guernica in a car showroom |publisher=Bbc.co.uk |date=15 February 2012 |accessdate=20 April 2013}}</ref> ''Guernica'' then returned briefly to France.\n\n===American tour===\nAfter Francisco Franco's victory in Spain, ''Guernica'' was sent to the United States to raise funds and support for Spanish refugees. The San Francisco Museum of Art (later renamed the [[San Francisco Museum of Modern Art]]) gave the work its first public appearance in the United States from 27 August to 19 September 1939. New York's [[Museum of Modern Art]] (MoMA) then mounted an exhibition from 15 November until 7 January 1940, entitled: ''Picasso: 40 Years of His Art''. The exhibition, which was organized by MoMA's director [[Alfred H. Barr]] in collaboration with the [[Art Institute of Chicago]], contained 344 works, including ''Guernica'' and its studies.<ref>Fluegel (1980), p. 350</ref>\n\nAt Picasso's request the safekeeping of ''Guernica'' was then entrusted to the Museum of Modern Art, and it was his expressed desire that the painting should not be delivered to Spain until liberty and democracy had been established in the country.<ref name=\"timeline\" /> Between 1939 and 1952, ''Guernica'' traveled extensively in the United States. Between 1953 and 1956 it was shown in [[Brazil]], then at the first Picasso retrospective in [[Milan]], Italy, and then in numerous other major European cities before returning to MoMA for a retrospective celebrating Picasso's 75th birthday. It then went to [[Chicago]] and [[Philadelphia]]. By this time, concern for the state of the painting resulted in a decision to keep it in one place: a room on MoMA's third floor, where it was accompanied by several of Picasso's preliminary studies and some of [[Dora Maar]]'s photographs of the work in progress. The studies and photos were often loaned for other exhibitions, but until 1981, ''Guernica'' itself remained at MoMA.<ref name=\"timeline\">[https://www.pbs.org/treasuresoftheworld/guernica/glevel_1/gtimeline.html Timeline], part of a series of web pages on ''Guernica'' in [[Public Broadcasting Service|PBS's]] ''Treasures of the World'' series. Accessed 16 July 2006.</ref>\n\nDuring the [[Vietnam War]], the room containing the painting became the site of occasional anti-war vigils. These were usually peaceful and uneventful, but on 28 February 1974, [[Tony Shafrazi]]\u2014ostensibly protesting Second Lieutenant [[William Calley]]'s petition for habeas corpus following his indictment and sentencing for the murder of 109 Vietnamese civilians during the [[My Lai massacre]]\u2014defaced the painting with red spray paint, painting the words \"KILL LIES ALL\". The paint was removed with relative ease from the varnished surface.<ref name=\"Hoberman 2004\">Hoberman 2004</ref>\n\n==Establishment in Spain==\nAs early as 1968, Franco had expressed an interest in having ''Guernica'' come to Spain.<ref name=\"timeline\" /> However, Picasso refused to allow this until the Spanish people again enjoyed a republic. He later added other conditions, such as the restoration of \"public liberties and democratic institutions\". Picasso died in 1973. Franco, ten years Picasso's junior, died two years later, in 1975. After Franco's death, Spain was transformed into a democratic [[constitutional monarchy]], ratified by [[Spanish Constitution of 1978|a new constitution]] in 1978. However, MoMA was reluctant to give up one of its greatest treasures and argued that a monarchy did not represent the republic that had been stipulated in Picasso's will as a condition for the painting's delivery. Under great pressure from a number of observers, MoMA finally ceded the painting to Spain in 1981. The Spanish historian [[Javier Tusell]] was one of the negotiators.\n\nUpon its arrival in Spain in September 1981,<ref name=uned/> it was first displayed behind bomb-and bullet-proof glass screens<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=8TO5wF6wUfoC&pg=PA294 Van Hensbergen, Gijs (2005) ''Guernica'' p. 305. Bloomsbury Publishing] At Google Books. Retrieved 18 July 2013.</ref> at the [[Cas\u00f3n del Buen Retiro]] in Madrid in time to celebrate the centenary of Picasso's birth, 25 October.<ref name=uned>{{in lang|es}} [http://portal.uned.es/portal/page?_pageid=93,24557421&_dad=portal&_schema=PORTAL \"30 a\u00f1os del \u201cGuernica\u201d en Espa\u00f1a\"] [[Universidad Nacional de Educaci\u00f3n a Distancia]] (UNED). Retrieved 18 July 2013.</ref> The exhibition was visited by almost a million people in the first year.<ref>{{in lang|es}} [http://elpais.com/diario/1982/09/10/cultura/400456802_850215.html \"Un mill\u00f3n de personas ha visto el 'Guernica' en el Cas\u00f3n del Buen Retiro\"] ''[[El Pa\u00eds]]''. Retrieved 18 July 2013.</ref> Since that time there has never been any attempted vandalism or other security threat to the painting.\n[[File:Mural del Gernika.jpg|right|thumb|A tiled wall in Gernika claims ''\"Guernica\" Gernikara'', \"The ''Guernica'' (painting) to Gernika.\"]]\nIn 1992, the painting was moved from the [[Museo del Prado]] to a purpose-built gallery at the [[Museo Nacional Centro de Arte Reina Sof\u00eda]], both in Madrid, along with about two dozen preparatory works.<ref name=his>[http://www.museodelprado.es/en/la-institucion/the-extension/el-cason-del-buen-retiro/historia/ The Cas\u00f3n del Buen Retiro: History] [[Museo del Prado]]. Retrieved 18 July 2013.</ref> This action was controversial in Spain, since Picasso's will stated that the painting should be displayed at the Prado. However, the move was part of a transfer of all of the Prado's collections of art after the early 19th century to other nearby buildings in the city for reasons of space; the Reina Sof\u00eda, which houses the capital's national collection of 20th-century art, was the natural place to move it to.\nAt the Reina Sof\u00eda, the painting has roughly the same protection as any other work.<ref name=\"Martin\">[http://www.picassoswar.com/interview.html Author interview] on Russell Martin's ''Picasso's War'' site. Accessed 16 July 2006.</ref>\n\n[[Basque nationalism|Basque nationalists]] have advocated that the picture should be brought to the Basque country,<ref name=\"ElMundoIbarretxe\">''[http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2007/06/29/cultura/1183129952.html Ibarretxe reclama 'para siempre' el 'Guernica']'', ''[[El Mundo (Spain)|El Mundo]]'', 29 June 2007.</ref> especially after the building of the [[Guggenheim Bilbao Museum]]. Officials at the Reina Sof\u00eda claim<ref name=\"ElMundoMncars\">''[http://www.elmundo.es/elmundo/2006/06/22/cultura/1150974391.html El Patronato del Reina Sof\u00eda rechaza la cesi\u00f3n temporal del 'Guernica' al Gobierno vasco]'', ''El Mundo'', 22 June 2006.</ref> that the canvas is now thought to be too fragile to move. Even the staff of the Guggenheim do not see a permanent transfer of the painting as possible, although the Basque government continues to support the possibility of a temporary exhibition in [[Bilbao]].<ref name=\"Martin\" />\n\n==Tapestry at the United Nations==\n\n[[File:Guernica at the Whitechapel - geograph.org.uk - 1593698.jpg|thumb|The tapestry, at the [[Whitechapel Gallery]] in 2009]]\n\nA full-size [[tapestry]] copy of Picasso's ''Guernica'', by {{ill|Jacqueline de la Baume D\u00fcrrbach|WD=Q32979529}},<ref name=\"IPoG\">{{Cite news |title=In praise of ... Guernica |work=The Guardian |accessdate = 2017-07-12 |date=2009-03-26 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2009/mar/26/pablo-picasso-guernica-spain-war }}</ref> is hung at the [[Headquarters of the United Nations]] in [[New York City]] at the entrance to the [[United Nations Security Council|Security Council]] room. It was displayed first from 1985 to 2009, and returned in 2015. It was commissioned in 1955 by [[Nelson Rockefeller]], since Picasso refused to sell him the original.<ref>Conrad, Peter. [https://www.theguardian.com/theobserver/2004/oct/03/art \"A scream we can't ignore\"], ''The Guardian'', 10 March 2004.</ref> The tapestry was placed on loan to the United Nations by the Rockefeller estate in 1985.<ref>Campbell (2009), 29.</ref> The tapestry is less monochromatic than the original and uses several shades of brown.\n\nOn 5 February 2003 a large blue curtain was placed to cover this work at the UN, so that it would not be visible in the background when [[Colin Powell]] and [[John Negroponte]] gave press conferences at the United Nations.<ref>Kennedy (2009).</ref> On the following day, it was claimed that the curtain was placed there at the request of television news crews, who had complained that the wild lines and screaming figures made for a bad backdrop, and that a horse's hindquarters appeared just above the faces of any speakers. Some diplomats, however, in talks with journalists claimed that the Bush administration pressured UN officials to cover the tapestry, rather than have it in the background while Powell or other US diplomats argued for war on Iraq.<ref name=\"Cohen_2003\">Cohen (2003).</ref> In a critique of the covering, columnist Alejandro Escalona hypothesized that ''Guernica''{{'}}s \"unappealing m\u00e9nage of mutilated bodies and distorted faces proved to be too strong for articulating to the world why the US was going to war in Iraq\", while referring to the work as \"an inconvenient masterpiece.\"<ref name = \"75years\" />\n\nOn 17 March 2009, Deputy Spokesperson for the Secretary-General Marie Okabe announced that the ''Guernica'' tapestry had been moved to a gallery in London in advance of extensive renovations at UN Headquarters. The ''Guernica'' tapestry was the showcase piece for the grand reopening of the [[Whitechapel Gallery]]. It was located in the 'Guernica room' which was originally part of the old Whitechapel Library.<ref>Hensbergen (2009).</ref> In 2012 the tapestry was on temporary loan to the [[San Antonio Museum of Art]] in [[San Antonio, Texas]] from the Rockefeller family.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.samuseum.org|title=San Antonio Museum of Art - Home|first=San Antonio Museum of|last=Art|website=Samuseum.org|accessdate=22 December 2017}}</ref>\nIt was returned to the UN by March 2015.<ref>Remnick, David (2015). [http://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/03/23/todays-woman \"Today's Woman\"], ''The New Yorker'', 23 March 2015.</ref>\n\n==Significance and legacy==\n{{quote box| quote = ''Guernica'' is to painting what [[Ludwig van Beethoven|Beethoven]]'s [[Symphony No. 9 (Beethoven)|Ninth Symphony]] is to music: a cultural<br />icon that speaks to mankind not only against war but also of hope and peace.<br />It is a reference when speaking about genocide from [[El Mozote massacre|El Salvador]] to [[Srebrenica massacre|Bosnia]].\n|source = Alejandro Escalona, on the 75th anniversary of the painting's creation<ref name = \"75years\">Escalona, Alejandro. [http://www.huffingtonpost.com/alejandro-escalona/75-years-of-picassos-guernica-_b_1538776.html 75 years of Picasso's Guernica: An Inconvenient Masterpiece], ''[[The Huffington Post]]'', 23 May 2012.</ref>}}\nDuring the 1970s, ''Guernica'' was a symbol for Spaniards of both the end of the Franco regime following Franco's death, and of [[Basque nationalism]]. The [[Basque National Liberation Movement|Basque left]] has repeatedly used imagery from the picture. An example is the organization [[Etxerat]], which uses a reversed image of the lamp as its symbol.<ref>{{cite web|title=Etxerat|url=http://www.etxerat.eus/index.php/eu/txostenak/hilabetekaria|publisher=Etxerat|accessdate=17 March 2016}}</ref>\n\nWorks inspired by ''Guernica'' include [[Goshka Macuga]]'s ''The Nature of the Beast'' (2009\u201310), which used the Whitechapel-hosted [[Guernica (Picasso)#Tapestry at the United Nations|United Nations ''Guernica'' tapestry]]; ''The Keiskamma Guernicas'' (2010\u20132017); and Erica Luckert's theatrical production of ''Guernica'' (2011\u201312).{{citation needed|date=February 2018}} Art and design historian Dr Nicola Ashmore curated an exhibition, ''Guernica Remakings'', at the [[University of Brighton]] galleries from 29 July 2017 to 23 August 2017.{{citation needed|date=February 2018}}\n\nIn 2016, the British art critic [[Jonathan Jones (journalist)|Jonathan Jones]] called the painting a \"Cubist apocalypse\" and stated that Picasso \"was trying to show the truth so viscerally and permanently that it could outstare the daily lies of the age of dictators.\"<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/artanddesign/jonathanjonesblog/2016/oct/12/picasso-guernica-aleppo-syria ''As Aleppo burns in this age of lies, Picasso's Guernica still screams the truth about war'']</ref><ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/long_reads/nazi-war-crime-guernica-80-anniversary-bombing-spain-picasso-hitler-franco-a7704916.html ''Eighty years later, the Nazi war crime in Guernica still matters - The grim anniversary of the bombing is a reminder of humanity's continuing capacity for evil'']</ref>\n\n''Guernica'' has become a universal and powerful symbol warning humanity against the suffering and devastation of war.<ref name = \"75years\" /> Moreover, the fact that there are no obvious references to the specific attack has contributed to making its message universal and timeless.<ref name = \"75years\" />\n\n==See also==\n* [[Guernica (sculpture)|''Guernica'']], 1937 sculpture by [[Ren\u00e9 Ich\u00e9]].\n\n==References and sources==\n;References\n{{reflist}}\n;Sources\n{{Refbegin|30em}}\n* [[Rudolf Arnheim|Arnheim, Rudolf]]. (1973). ''The Genesis of a Painting: Picasso'